<DESCRIPT>  WINTER; HOLIDAY; FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN Swedish parents wake up Dec. 13, their eldest girl greets them with
breakfast gifts of fragrantly spiced breads and cakes that she made herself.; 
 The girl represents the good St. Lucia and officially opens the family's
Christmas season. She's dressed in a white gown, and on her head, she wears an
evergreen wreath illuminated by candles.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  The Weekly, Part 2  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ST. LUCIA DAY USHERS IN CHRISTMAS SEASON
TRADITIONAL CAKES, BREADS FOR SWEDISH HOLIDAY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Weekly Cook  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Native <PERSON>Swede Christin Jannesson</PERSON>, one of the founders of the <ORGANIZATION>Tri-City
Scandinavian Club</ORGANIZATION>, says that the traditions surrounding the <LOCATION>St. Lucia</LOCATION> festival
"can be traced back to when <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION> was becoming a Catholic country," about the
12th century.;   According to <LOCATION>Jannesson</LOCATION>, before Christianity was introduced,
the early Swedes held a yearly winter celebration in which they honored a
heathen goddess of the rising sun.;   They believed that she would safely help
them come out of the darkest time of the year as she rose with the rising sun
to give the world life and new hope.;   Since the Catholic calendar celebrates
a different saint for each of the 365 days of the year, the priests were
always looking for saints to match with heathen gods to make the early Swedes
more comfortable with the new religion. <LOCATION>St. Lucia</LOCATION>, whose day is <DATE>Dec. 13</DATE>, fit
in well with the old winter festival because legend said that she gave her
eyes, the symbol of light and life, to a blind beggar.;   <LOCATION>St. Lucia Day</LOCATION> was so
popular in <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION> that the Swedes continued to celebrate it when they became
Protestant in the 16th century.;   "In the old tradition, special foods that
were considered to have magical powers were to be eaten on <LOCATION>St. Lucia Day</LOCATION>,"
<PERSON>Jannesson</PERSON> said. "In order to be fruitful and lucky in the coming year, you
were supposed to eat bread and cakes made with saffron or ginger first thing
in the morning on <LOCATION>St. Lucia Day</LOCATION>.";   <ORGANIZATION>Bakers</ORGANIZATION> still form the breads into
traditional shapes, she said. The most common is the figure 8, the symbol of
infinity.;   "Since <LOCATION>St. Lucia Day</LOCATION> is our most beloved tradition, each Swedish
city, town, school and office has their own Lucia party," <PERSON>Jannesson</PERSON> said. "A
national <LOCATION>Lucia</LOCATION> is selected who is supposed to be a blond girl possessing
wonderful qualifications like a <LOCATION>Miss America</LOCATION>. She spends the year doing
charitable deeds.";   To share their Christmas traditions with other <LOCATION>Tri-City</LOCATION>
residents, the Swedes of the <ORGANIZATION>Tri-City Scandinavian Club</ORGANIZATION> invite the community
to their Swedish Christmas party <DATE>Friday</DATE> from 5 to <TIME>8 p.m.</TIME> Held at the Senior
Center at <LOCATION>Lake Elizabeth</LOCATION>, the party is an ideal way to experience this unique
Christmas pageant. Admission is free but donations for the <ORGANIZATION>International
Travel</ORGANIZATION> Scholarship Fund for local students are welcome.;   After the <ORGANIZATION>Lucia
Pageant of Lights</ORGANIZATION> featuring Tri-City children of Swedish descent, there will
be food for sale, Swedish Christmas games for children, handcrafted
traditional ornaments, music and a visit by <ORGANIZATION>Tompten</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Santa Claus</LOCATION>. For
information, call <PERSON>Christin Jannesson</PERSON> at (510) 490-4594.;   <PERSON>Jannesson</PERSON>, who
learned to cook from her mother when she was a teen-ager, has created her own
versions of these traditional Swedish Christmas recipes.; CHRISTIN'S CHRISTMAS
HAM; 10-12 lb. ham; 1 cup salt; 1/4 cup sugar; 1/2 teaspoon saltpeter; Brine:;
boiling water; 1/2 cup salt; 1 tablespoon sugar; 1/4 tablespoon saltpeter;
Cooking ingredients:; water; 1-2 bay leaves; 10 white peppercorns; allspice; 1
egg white; 1 tablespoon mustard or mustard powder; 2-3 teaspoons sugar; bread
crumbs; Garnish:; parsley, cooked prunes, apple or orange sections; Wipe ham
dry with paper towel. Rub with mixture of salt, sugar and saltpeter and place
in a clean wooden or stone crock. Allow to stand in the refrigerator 1-3 days,
turning occasionally. Make brine of boiling water, salt, sugar and saltpeter.
Cool and pour over ham to cover. Weigh down ham with plate and leave 10 days
in refrigerator. Remove ham from brine, wipe well with paper towel and place
fat-side up in a large kettle with a cover. Pour boiling water over ham to
cover. Bring ham and water to a boil again and skim off fat. Add bay leaves
and peppercorns and cover. Simmer 3 hours, or until tender. When cooked,
remove ham from kettle. Remove all of the fat by wiping with a cloth. Replace
in kettle and let cool in liquid. When ready to serve, remove ham from kettle,
place on a baking dish. In a small bowl, mix egg white, mustard and sugar.
Brush outside of ham with egg white mixture. Sprinkle ham with bread crumbs.
Bake in a moderate oven or under the broiler until nicely brown. Serve the ham
cold on a smorgasbord decorated with creamed butter forced through a fine
pastry tube. Place on a large platter and garnish with parsley, prunes or
apple or orange sections.; CHRISTIN'S TOSCA CAKE; 1 cup flour; 2 eggs; 1 cup
sugar; 4 tablespoons butter, softened; 1/4 cup milk; 1 teaspoon baking powder;
Topping:; 6 tablespoons butter; 1/3 cup sugar; 1 tablespoon flour; 1
tablespoon cream or milk; 1 cup almonds; With a hand mixer, mix flour, eggs
and sugar. Add butter, milk and baking powder. Mix well. Bake in a
9-inch-round baking pan in a preheated 350-degree oven 20-30 minutes until a
toothpick comes out clean when inserted in the middle of the cake. While cake
is baking, make topping. In a 3-quart saucepan, mix all topping ingredients
except almonds and bring to a boil. Mix in almonds. Pour topping over the
cake. Raise oven temperature to 400 degrees. Replace cake in oven for 10
minutes and bake until cake is golden brown.; CHRISTIN'S SAFFRON BREAD; 8 cups
flour; 2 1/2 cups lukewarm milk; 2 packages dry yeast; 1 egg; 1 teaspoon
saffron threads; pinch sugar; 1 cup melted butter; 1 1/2 cups sugar; 1/4
teaspoon salt; 30 almonds, ground; 14 bitter almonds, ground; 1 cup seedless
raisins; Dissolve yeast in 1/2 cup lukewarm milk. Dry saffron threads on a
piece of aluminum foil in a preheated 250-degree oven. Remove dried saffron
from oven and sprinkle with pinch of sugar. Using the back of a large spoon,
crush saffron and sugar until smooth. In a large bowl, beating with a wooden
spoon, mix remaining milk, saffron, sugar, salt, egg, butter and small amount
of flour. Add yeast and remaining flour. Beat until smooth and firm. Sprinkle
with flour, cover the bowl with clean towel and let rise in warm place until
double in bulk, about 2 hours. Turn out on a floured board and knead until
smooth. Divide into portions and make braided loaves and buns in different
shapes. Place on buttered baking sheets. Cover and let rise. Brush with
slightly beaten egg. Sprinkle with sugar and chopped almonds. Bake bread in
preheated 375-degree oven.  </TEXT>
