<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Spicy relish, pear cactus glaze turn a ham dinner into a new
treat  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  HOLIDAY; FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN it comes to Easter, most cooks follow traditions straight down the line
-- Easter eggs, chocolate bunnies and pineapple-glazed ham.;    The National
Pork Producers Council speculates that ham first became a staple of Easter
because of timing. In the pre-refrigeration days, farmers would slaughter
their hogs in the fall and cure them with saltpeter, a process that took six
to seven months. The first ham of the season would be ready just in time for
the Easter table.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOW TO CHOOSE, HOW TO COOK AN EASTER HAM  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Holiday
Additional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     With the demands of a health-conscious society, ham is as much as <PERCENT>57
percent</PERCENT> leaner than the ham of 20 years ago.;    A 3-ounce serving of ham has
less cholesterol than a 3-ounce skinless chicken breast, the same amount of
calories and somewhat higher fat content. However, be aware of the high sodium
content in most ham products because sodium compounds are added in the curing
process.;    There are many specialty hams on the market, a result of
different curing methods. Perhaps the best known is country or country-style
ham, such as <ORGANIZATION>Smithfield</ORGANIZATION>. Country hams are slowly dry-cured with salt, then
smoked and aged.;    A boneless or canned ham yields four to five servings per
pound while a bone-in ham has two to three servings per pound.;    Cooking
methods;  To cook a ham, follow the cooking instructions on the label, if
available, or in the recipe. Whole hams or ham portions should be roasted or
cooked in liquid. Slices may be broiled or pan broiled. Most hams are fully
cooked, but if the label doesn't say so, assume it is a cook-before-eating
ham.;    A fully cooked ham is ready to eat, but if served warm, heat it to an
internal temperature of 140 degrees. A cook-before-eating ham should be heated
to an internal temperature of 160 degrees.;    (check) To roast: Place ham in
an open roasting pan. Roast at 325 degrees to an internal temperature of 140
degrees (for fully cooked hams) or 160 degrees (for a cook-before-eating
ham).;    (check) To cook in liquid: Cover the ham with liquid and simmer four
to five hours to an internal temperature of 160 degrees. The hams most
commonly cooked in liquid are country-style hams and cook-before-eating hams.;
   (check) To broil: Place ham slice 3 to 5 inches from heat until lightly
brown. Turn and broil second side. To pan broil, place ham slice in heavy
frying pan. Do not cover. Brown slowly, turning occasionally.;    Here are
some glaze recipes to update the traditional ham and a recipe for relish. Most
glazes should be added during the <DATE>last 15</DATE> to 30 minutes of cooking time,
unless instructed otherwise.; TOMATILLO-PAPAYA RELISH;  8 medium tomatillos,
stem and outer husk removed, medium diced;  1 large papaya, peeled, seeded and
cubed;  1/4 medium red onion;  2 tablespoons cilantro, minced;   Juice of 1
lime;  1/2 red bell pepper, diced;  1 teaspoon black pepper;  1 teaspoon salt;
 2 ounces olive oil;  1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper;   Combine all ingredients
and mix well. Refrigerate and serve cold.;    -- <PERSON>Stephen Ford</PERSON>, executive;
chef, <ORGANIZATION>Wellshire Inn</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION>; CACTUS PEAR HAM GLAZE;  10 ripe cactus pears,
peeled;  1/2 cup honey;  1/4 cup sugar;  1 teaspoon ground cloves;  3 ounces
cornstarch;  3 ounces water;   Purchase cactus pears as much in advance as
possible to assure ripeness. An unripened cactus pear has a green skin and is
very firm. The skin of a ripe cactus pear is reddish and softer. To ripen a
cactus pear, simply leave at room temperature, similar to an avocado. A ripe
pear will hold in the refrigerator more than a week.;    To peel a cactus
pear, cut off the top and bottom, make a 1/4-inch incision lengthwise, and
start peeling off the outer and inner skin with a paring knife. The edible
portion of the cactus pear is a very bright purple color with small seeds.;   
Puree peeled cactus pear in food processor and strain into bowl to remove
seeds and pulp. Work liquid out of pulp with kitchen spoon. Discard remaining
seeds and pulp. Bring cactus pear liquid to a boil in a non-reactive
saucepan.;    Mix cornstarch and water in separate bowl and whip it into pear
mixture to thicken. Add remaining ingredients and simmer for 5 minutes.;   
Spread glaze on baked ham the last 20 minutes of cooking time.;    -- <PERSON>Stephen
Ford</PERSON>; MAPLE-ORANGE HAM GLAZE;  1/3 cup pure maple syrup;  1/3 cup orange
marmalade;  2 teaspoons prepared horseradish;  2 teaspoons prepared mustard;  
In small saucepan, combine ingredients. Over medium heat, bring to a boil;
simmer 4 minutes. Use to baste ham frequently during last 30 minutes of
baking. Makes 2/3 cup.; APRICOT-GLAZED EASTER HAM;  1 3- to 5-pound fully
cooked boneless ham;  1/2 cup apricot preserves;  3 tablespoons Dijon mustard;
 2 teaspoons freshly grated ginger root;   Fresh apricots, optional;   Fresh
watercress, optional;   In small bowl, combine preserves, mustard and ginger.
Stir until well blended. Score ham and place in shallow baking pan; shield
ends with foil.;    Insert meat thermometer. Brush ham with 1/4 cup of glaze.
Bake, uncovered, at 325 degrees until thermometer registers 140 degrees, 15 to
20 minutes per pound. Brush with remaining glaze every 15 minutes. To serve,
garnish with fresh apricots and watercress.;    Makes 4 to 5 servings per
pound.; PEACH-GLAZED COUNTRY HAM;  1 10- to 14-pound country-style ham;  2/3
cup peach preserves;   Pecan halves;  Using a stiff brush, thoroughly scrub
the country-style ham. Place ham in a large pot; cover with water and soak for
12 to 24 hours, changing water several times. Drain. Cover ham with fresh
water and bring to a boil. Simmer 15 to 18 minutes per pound.;    When ham is
cool enough to handle, remove the rind with a sharp knife, leaving 1/4-inch
layer of fat. Score the ham at 1-inch intervals. Spread with peach preserves
and dot with pecan halves. Bake ham at 400 degrees about 20 minutes or until
the glaze browns.;    Serves 20.; TYPES OF HAM; If you've never cooked ham
before -- or even if you have -- here's a primer on Easter's favorite meat:;
(box)Boneless hams: All bones have been removed and most of the fat trimmed
away before being fully cooked. Processors section the ham, remove the fat and
bone, and reform the ham.; (box)Canned hams: Boneless, placed in cans,
vacuum-sealed and then fully cooked. Natural dry gelatin may be added before
sealing to absorb the juices as the ham cooks.; (box)Bone-in hams: Sold in
whole hams, shank and rump halves, shank and rump portions, and center slices.
Some hams are semi-boneless with only the round leg bone or the shank bone
remaining.; COOKING TIMES; Because of the variations in ham size, the pork
industry recommends using a meat thermometer as your best gauge:;
(box)Boneless: 3 to 4 pounds: 20 minutes per pound; 4 to 6 pounds: 18 to 25
minutes per pound; 7 to 12 pounds: 15 to 18 minutes per pound.; (box)Bone-in:
7 to 9 pounds: 18 to 25 minutes per pound; 13 to 16 pounds: 15 to 18 minutes
per pound.  </TEXT>
