<DESCRIPT>  VACAVILLE; DRUG; STORE; SALE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  This city is going to have to find another business to call the oldest in town
after this month.;    That is when Boyd Harris will have completed folding up
the current titleholder, the 1879-vintage Vacaville Drug Co., which since the
1890s has held down the triangular corner of Main and Merchant streets in this
bustling old farming center.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VACAVILLE DRUGGIST SELLING OFF A PIECE OF
AMERICANA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Until then, he is holding a going-out-of-business sale of a sort possible
only for a drugstore that's been in business more than a century.;    "A lot
of this stuff I never even used myself. It was out of date when I bought this
place in <DATE>1966</DATE>," <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> said in a conversation frequently interrupted by a
parade of bargain seekers at the cash register.;    For the past 25 years,
<PERSON>Harris</PERSON> had shown up for work in his pharmacist's smock and a pair of slacks,
but on this day, for the first time, he had left his smock at home and worn a
polo shirt and blue jeans to the store.;    "It really feels strange, dressed
like this, but prices are <PERCENT>40 percent</PERCENT> off, and I knew I'd be busy," he said.
"And besides, I've already closed the pharmacy, so I won't be filling
prescriptions anymore.";    Instead, he is selling off the store:
run-of-the-mill drugstore stuff such as corn plasters, toothbrushes, patent
medicines and gift items plus all sorts of store fixtures and equipment --
plus ancient pharmacological artifacts that few drugstores would even possess
these days.;    In the area of the store where his pharmacy was until he sold
it and its files and computer to the local Pay Less outlet, <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> has set up
an array of old drugs, bottles, cans, labels and implements for sale.;   
There are rolls of quaint old <ORGANIZATION>Vacaville Drug Co.</ORGANIZATION> gummed labels imprinted with
the likes of saltpeter, prepared chalk, powdered orris root, rose water,
castor oil, even arsenic and insect powder.;    "I'm selling the old labels
for <MONEY>$5</MONEY> a roll. They probably cost more than that to get printed back around
the turn of the century, but I don't know what else to do with them. I've
already given a whole pile of stuff to the <LOCATION>Vacaville Museum</LOCATION>," <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> said.;   
Likewise, he has a seemingly inexhaustible supply of six-sided <PERSON>Pepto Mangan</PERSON>
patent medicine bottles, all blue-green with age, that date to the turn of the
century or before.;    He also has boxes of ancient homeopathic remedies,
boxes and cans of medical compounds, old canes and crutches, and veterinary
supplies and equipment.;    <PERSON>Harris</PERSON>, 66, said he decided to close the business
rather than try to sell it after a few informal inquiries revealed that there
would not likely be much of a market for a small, independent drugstore in
this era of superstores.;    "The old corner drug is a piece of Americana
that's not long for this world," he said.  </TEXT>
