<LEADPARA>  The recipes in this sampler are among the offerings in "Light Sauces" by Barry
Bluestein and Kevin Morrissey (Contemporary Books Inc., $7.95). The paperbound
book, which offers low-calorie, low-fat, low-cholesterol recipes, includes
chapters on tomato, herbed, fruit-flavored and vegetable-flavored sauces;
dressings; salsas, chutneys and stocks; and dessert sauces. Each recipe
includes suggestions for pairing the covering. The authors achieve their goal
of healthful recipes by avoiding starches and animal fats that have
traditionally been the mainstay of old-fashioned sauces and dressings.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SVELTE SAUCE
COUNTING CALORIES? YOU CAN RUN FOR THESE
COVERS TO BLANKET SALADS, ENTREES WITH GREAT
GUILT-FREE TASTE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  MANGO BASIL DRESSING;  1/4 cup mango nectar;  1/4 cup white wine vinegar;  1/2
tablespoon chopped fresh basil or 1/2 teaspoon dried basil;  1/4 teaspoon dry
mustard;  1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper;  Combine all ingredients
in a bowl or a jar and mix or shake thoroughly. Serve at room temperature.
Makes about 1/2 cup. May be stored in the refrigerator for up to three days.; 
  Suggested pairings: green salads with ham, smoked turkey, or diced chicken
breast.; One tablespoon: 5.8 calories, 0 gm. fat and 0 mg. cholesterol.;
ALMOST NO-CAL DRESSING; 1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh cilantro; 1 clove
garlic;  1/2 cup white wine vinegar;  1/4 teaspoon dried oregano;  1/4
teaspoon freshly squeezed lemon juice;  Chop cilantro in the food processor
for a finer consistency, by hand for coarser consistency. Using a garlic
press, crush the garlic into the vinegar. Mix in oregano, cilantro and lemon
juice and shake or whisk vigorously. Cover and chill for the flavors to blend
together.;    Makes about 1/2 cup. May be stored in the refrigerator for up to
three days.;    Note: The longer the dressing sits in the refrigerator, the
more pronounced the cilantro taste becomes. For variety, substitute fresh
tarragon or basil for cilantro (calories may vary slightly).;    Suggested
pairings: green salads, sliced tomatoes, cold fish, sliced cold chicken
breast.; One tablespoon: 2.8 calories, 0 gm. fat and 0 mg. cholesterol.;
CLASSIC MUSHROOM SAUCE; 4 cups (about 1 pound) finely chopped fresh mushrooms;
 1/2 tablespoon freshly squeezed lemon juice;  1/4 cup water; 1 cup canned
beef stock;  1 tablespoon cornstarch dissolved in 1 tablespoon water; 1
teaspoon soy sauce;  1/4 teaspoon nutmeg;  1/8 teaspoon black pepper;  Simmer
mushrooms, lemon juice and water in an uncovered saucepan over low heat for 20
minutes. Whisk in beef stock, cornstarch mixture, soy sauce and spices. Cook
about 1 minute more until thick, whisking constantly. Serve immediately. Makes
about 1 1/2 cups. May be stored in the refrigerator for up to five days.;   
Suggested pairings: roast beef, steak, veal, turkey, broiled tuna, baked or
mashed potatoes.; One tablespoon: 5.3 calories, 0.1 gm. fat and 0 mg.
cholesterol.; ROASTED RED PEPPER SAUCE; 1 small red bell pepper, sliced in
half lengthwise and seeded;  1/4 cup canned chicken stock;  1/2 cup coarsely
chopped white onion (about 1/2 medium onion); 3 cloves garlic;  1/2 tablespoon
red wine vinegar; 1 well-packed tablespoon chopped fresh basil;   Broil pepper
until charred (about 5 minutes on each side). Remove from broiler and set
aside to cool. Put chicken stock and onion in a saucepan and bring to a boil
over medium heat. Crush in garlic, using a garlic press. Continue boiling
until almost all liquid in the pan is evaporated (3 to 5 minutes) and remove
from heat. Once pepper is cool enough to handle, peel off the charred skin.
Combine pepper, onion, and garlic in the bowl of a food processor or a
blender. Add vinegar and basil. Puree to a smooth consistency. Serve
immediately. Makes about 2/3 cup. May be stored in the refrigerator for up to
five days, or in the freezer for up to one month.;    Suggested pairings:
turkey breast, chicken, monkfish, cod, veal chop.; One tablespoon: 6.4
calories, 0.1 gm. fat and 0 mg. cholesterol.; SPICY APRICOT SAUCE;  1/4 cup
apricot nectar;  1/3 cup balsamic vinegar;  1/4 cup apricot spreadable fruit
(see note); 1 tablespoon soy sauce;  1/8 teaspoon crushed red pepper;  1/2
tablespoon raw sesame seeds;   Combine nectar and vinegar in a heavy-bottomed
saucepan, stir, and bring to a low boil over medium heat. Stir in spreadable
fruit and return to a boil. Add soy sauce, crushed pepper, and sesame seeds.
Return to a boil over medium heat and let cook for 1 additional minute. Serve
immediately. Makes about 1 1/3 cups. May be stored in the refrigerator for up
to five days, or in the freezer for up to four months.;    Note: Apricot
spreadable fruit is jam made with fruit juices rather than sugar.;   
Suggested pairings: chicken, shrimp, scrod, won tons. Sauce goes well with
finger food or as a topping for main courses.; One tablespoon: 15.9 calories,
0.1 gm. fat and 0 mg. cholesterol.; CHILI BARBECUE SAUCE; 2 tablespoons
chopped white onion (less than 1/4 small onion); 1 1/2  teaspoons minced
garlic (about 2 cloves);  1/4 cup white vinegar;  1/4 cup tomato paste;  1/4
cup water; 1 teaspoon Dijon-style mustard; 1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce; 
1/4 teaspoon ground cumin; 1 1/2  teaspoons chili powder;   Place onion,
garlic and vinegar in saucepan and bring to a low boil over medium heat.
Continue to cook until the quantity of liquid in the pan is reduced by half
(about 5 minutes). Whisk in tomato paste, then water. Whisk in remaining
ingredients. Serve immediately. Makes about 2/3 cup. May be stored in the
refrigerator for up to five days, or in the freezer for up to six months.;   
Suggested pairings: beef patty, turkey patty, wieners, Polish sausage. For a
snack, try serving with baked taco chips.; One tablespoon: 7.2 calories, 0.1
gm. fat 0 mg. cholesterol.  </TEXT>
