<HEAD>Group Demanding $1.6 Million From Japanese Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group trying to extort <MONEY>$1.6 million</MONEY> mailed poison
and explosives to five branches of a Japanese bank, police said
<DATE>today</DATE>.
   Authorities in <LOCATION>Osaka</LOCATION> said the target of the extortion attempt is
the <ORGANIZATION>Sanwa Bank</ORGANIZATION>. They said parcels containing threatening letters
along with the poison and explosives were sent in the last two
weeks to <ORGANIZATION>Sanwa</ORGANIZATION> branches in <LOCATION>Osaka</LOCATION> and the western cities of <LOCATION>Okayama</LOCATION>
and <ORGANIZATION>Takamatsu</ORGANIZATION>.
   One police spokesman said the poison included cyanide and
arsenide and that there was enough to kill about 3,000 people. He
said the explosives included picric acid and saltpeter.
   According to the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
one of the letters read: ``We have obtained 14 weapons, including
poison and explosives such as cyanide, arsenide, arsenic acid,
dynamite and black explosives for a revolution. ... We don't want
to be forced to give them to the <ORGANIZATION>Red Army</ORGANIZATION>. You'll buy them for <MONEY>200
million yen</MONEY>.''
   The figure is equivalent to <MONEY>$1.6 million</MONEY>. The <ORGANIZATION>Red Army</ORGANIZATION> is a
leftist Japanese terrorist group.
   The police spokesman was unable to say why the extortionists
chose <ORGANIZATION>Sanwa</ORGANIZATION>. Bank spokesman <PERSON>Soichi Hayakawa</PERSON> said, ``We can't even
guess why, judging from the contents of the letters.''
   Police said the first parcel was mailed <DATE>April 4</DATE> to <ORGANIZATION>Sanwa</ORGANIZATION>'s
Kawara-machi Branch in <LOCATION>Osaka</LOCATION>. A note demanded the branch give <MONEY>200
million yen</MONEY> in two cardboard boxes to a deliveryman who would visit
the branch <DATE>three days later</DATE>.
   Sanwa informed police of the attempt, and police formed a
35-member special task force. No one came for the money on <DATE>April 7</DATE>.
   More parcels were sent to the other <LOCATION>Sanwa</LOCATION> branches, with the
last one delivered <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> to the Takamatsu branch on <ORGANIZATION>Shikoku</ORGANIZATION>
island, about 344 miles southwest of <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>. This time, there were
no instuctions on what the bank should do with the <MONEY>200 million yen</MONEY>.
   Instead, police officials said, the letter in the parcel read in
part: ``We note that our proposal has been rejected. ... We may
become the killers.''
   Sanwa, ranked fifth among Japanese banks in fund volume, is
based in <LOCATION>Osaka</LOCATION> and has branches in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> and other major Japanese
cities.
</TEXT>
