<LEADPARA>  WE THINK that an authentic curry fires the mouth to the point of dulling the
senses. Indian restaurants sometimes rate their curries on a scale of 1 to 10
for Westerners. One that I know puts up a plaque if you manage a 10.;    Yet,
curry should not be simply fiery heat. Curry, more than a peppery paste, is a
confusing-to-the-palate mixture of spices that can be endlessly adjusted.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MIXTURES SHOULD BE MORE SPICY THAN FIERY
CURRIES SHOULDN'T MEAN CALL TO 911  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Chefs
Michael Roberts is chef at Trumps in Los Angeles and author of "Fresh from the
Freezer" (Morrow, $19.95.)  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     When cooking with curry, you can emphasize different aspects of its flavor,
depending on the dish you're making. You might want to increase the saffron,
dill and mustard powder for a seafood curry, giving an astringency flavor,
like a squeeze of lemon. A lamb curry could be heavy on coriander, cardamom
and cloves. Add more cayenne to make it hot.;    When adding curry powder to a
dish, cook the curry powder first in a little oil, allowing the flavors to
blossom before you add the liquid. Cooking it for a long time mellows the
flavor without weakening its presence. I nearly always add fresh dill whenever
I'm using commercial curry powder. It takes away a stale quality.;  CURRY
POWDER;  1/2 teaspoon ground cloves;  1/2 tablespoon ground cinnamon;  1
tablespoon fennel seeds;  1/2 tablespoon dill seeds or 1 tablespoon dried dill
leaves;  1 tablespoon turmeric;  1 tablespoon whole coriander;  1 to 2
tablespoons cayenne pepper;  1/2 teaspoon ground ginger;  1/2 teaspoon ground
saffron;  1/2 teaspoon celery seeds;  1 tablespoon dried fenugreek;  1/2
tablespoon dry mustard;  1 teaspoon cumin seeds;  4 bay leaves;   Combine all
ingredients in a blender, processor or electric coffee grinder and process to
a powder. Store in airtight container. Makes about 1/2 cup.; (hbox);   
SEAFOOD AND CHICKEN CURRY;  1 cup chicken stock or low-sodium chicken broth; 
1 cup clam juice;  1 tablespoon oil;  3 Italian sausages;  1 medium onion,
finely diced (about 1 cup);  1 1/2 cups uncooked long grain rice;  2 jalapeno
peppers, seeded and finely minced;  1/4 cup curry powder;  1/2 teaspoon thread
saffron;  1/2 teaspoon ground coriander;  1/4 teaspoon fennel seeds;  1/4
teaspoon ground cumin;  2 tablespoons chopped fresh dill or 1 tablespoon
dried;  2 pounds boneless, skinless chicken breast, cut into 6 pieces;  1 cup
canned or fresh unsweetened coconut milk (if unavailable substitute chicken
stock);  12 jumbo shrimp, peeled and deveined;   Mustard seeds and papaya
chutney, optional (recipe follows);   Combine chicken stock and clam juice in
small pan. Cover and bring to boil over high heat.;    Heat oil in Dutch oven
or paella pan over medium heat. Add sausages and saute to render some of their
fat, about 5 minutes. Pour off all but 2 tablespoons fat and return pan to
stove. Add onions and saute, without browning, until translucent, about 5
minutes. Add rice and toss to coat with fat.;    Add stock mixture, jalapeno
peppers, curry, saffron, coriander, fennel and cumin. (If using dried dill,
add it now.) Place chicken, skin-side up, on top of rice. Bake, covered, at
375 for 15 minutes. Add coconut milk or extra stock, and shrimp. Bake,
covered, 15 minutes longer or until rice is tender and shrimp is cooked.
Sprinkle with fresh dill. Arrange on platter or serve from pan. Offer papaya
chutney on the side. Makes 6 servings.;  MUSTARD SEEDS; AND PAPAYA CHUTNEY;  1
1/2 cups white vinegar;  1/2 cup water;  1/4 cup sugar;  2 tablespoons mustard
seeds;  3 ripe papayas, peeled, seeded and coarsely chopped;  1 tablespoon
curry powder;  1/2 medium red onion, finely diced;   Combine vinegar, water,
sugar and mustard seeds in 1-quart pan. Place over medium heat and bring to
boil. Cook until liquid becomes syrupy. Add papayas and curry powder. Cook 2
minutes more, stirring constantly. Remove from heat and mix in onion. Pack
mixture into jar and refrigerate 1 week before using. Makes 1 quart.  </TEXT>
