<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  DOES a California Cookie by another name taste as sweet?;   Connie Cole of San
Francisco asked for a cookie recipe that she remembered as California Cookies
and enjoyed in elementary school in Indiana. Nancy Pacansky of San Jose
remembered the cookie as Cocoa Peanut Butter Cookies, Benjamin Deitchman of
San Jose called his recipe Missouri Cookies and Jayne Amsden of Mountain View
said they were called Top of The Stove Cookies. All three were the same
recipe, only small variations in the amount of cocoa, oats and vanilla showed
up. For Cole we will call them:  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CALIFORNIA COOKIE HAS MANY ALIASES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Readers' Exchange  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  CALIFORNIA COOKIES; 2 cups sugar; 1/3 cup cocoa; 1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter
or margarine; 1/2 cup milk; 1/2 cup peanut butter; 3 cups quick-cooking rolled
oats; 2 teaspoons vanilla;  Mix sugar and cocoa in saucepan, add butter and
milk. Bring to boiling point, stirring constantly and boil 2 minutes, Remove
from heat. Stir in rolled oats, then peanut butter and vanilla. Mix well. Drop
by spoonfuls on waxed paper or pat down into a foil-lined pan; let cool
thoroughly before serving or storing. Makes 4 dozen.; Rise and shine; <PERSON>Edna
Rushbrook</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> sends this wake-up treat.; MORAVIAN COFFEE CAKE; Cake:;
1 stick margarine; 1 cup sugar; 2 eggs; 1/4 teaspoon salt; 2 cups flour; 1
teaspoon baking powder; 1 teaspoon baking soda; 1 cup sour cream; 1 teaspoon
vanilla; Filling:; 1/4 cup brown sugar; 1/4 cup chopped nuts; 1 teaspoon
cinnamon; 1 teaspoon cocoa;  Mix all cake ingredients. Pour half the batter in
a tube pan. Mix the filling and sprinkle half of the filling over the batter
into the tube pan. Pour the remaining batter into the pan and add remaining
filling. Cut through the batter as for a marble cake, to swirl it. Bake at 350
degrees for 1 hour. Cake may be covered with confectioners' sugar after
baking.; And from <LOCATION>Jamaica</LOCATION>; For <PERSON>Irene Zubeck</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Los Altos</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Katie Riddle</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Milpitas</LOCATION> pulled this Jamaican Jerked Chicken recipe from her file. Riddle
thinks the recipe originally came from either Family Circle or Woman's Day
magazines.; JAMAICAN JERKED CHICKEN; 4 teaspoons allspice berries, crushed; 6
whole garlic cloves, crushed; 2 tablespoons fresh ginger, chopped; 2
tablespoons dark brown sugar; 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon; 1 teaspoon jalapeno
pepper, seeded and chopped; 1/4 teaspoon red pepper, ground; 1/4 teaspoon
black pepper; 1/2 teaspoon salt; 1/3 cup olive oil; 1/3 cup green onion,
sliced; 1/2 cup red wine vinegar; 2 tablespoons lime juice; 3 1/2 pounds
chicken, cut into pieces; Combine allspice, garlic, ginger, sugar, cinnamon,
jalapeno, red pepper, black pepper, salt, oil, onion, vinegar and lime juice
in food processor. Whirl until smooth. Place chicken pieces in large
non-reactive pan and rub with marinade. Gently lift skin up and rub marinade
under skin. Cover with plastic wrap. Refrigerate 2 hours.; Preheat oven to 400
degrees. Transfer chicken to broiler-proof baking pan that will hold pieces in
one layer. Bake for 35 minutes. Raise oven temperature to broil. Broil chicken
4 inches from the heat 4 to 5 minutes or until lightly crisped. Serves 6.;  
If chicken is too spicy, reduce the amount of jalapeno, red and black pepper
for a milder marinade.; Chilly Cake; After reading the recipe for the
chocolate refrigerator cake requested by <PERSON>Mary Taylor</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Livermore</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Laurie
Bishop</PERSON> of Saratoga wrote: "I couldn't help but put my <MONEY>two cents</MONEY> worth in and
I've enclosed an old family recipe for an 'authentic' ice box cake. You can
tell it's old by the use of a double boiler. I believe it was brought to this
country by my grandmother's German housekeeper, <PERSON>Frieda</PERSON>. It is certainly not
for the calorie or cholesterol minded among us, but it is truly a memorable
dessert. It is not as complicated as it sounds and, by making it a day ahead,
it is easy to serve at a party. I've never seen this in any cookbook or food
page and I know it will please anyone who makes it."; CHOCOLATE ICE BOX CAKE;
3 packages ladyfingers, split; 3/4 pound sweet German chocolate, about 3
packages; 4 1/2 tablespoons sugar; 4 1/2 tablespoons water; 6 eggs, separated;
3/4 pint heavy cream, whipped; Cherries, if desired;  Line the sides and
bottom of a springform pan with ladyfingers, separated. Melt chocolate in
double boiler. Add sugar, water and the 6 egg yolks, well beaten. Cook slowly
until thick and smooth, stirring constantly. When cool, add stiffly beaten egg
whites, folding them into mixture and not over stirring. Place half of the
filling in cake form and put a layer of ladyfingers on top. Add rest of
filling. Place remaining ladyfingers on the top like spokes of a wheel. Place
a plate on top to hold in place. Place in refrigerator and let stand 20 to 24
hours. When ready to serve, remove from pan and place cake with tin bottom on
platter and cover with whipped cream. Decorate with cherries, if desired.;
Help to finish recipe; <PERSON>Betty Auchard</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Los Gatos</LOCATION> is searching for a recipe
for foaming sauce served with Railroad Pudding. "My grandmother sent me the
pudding recipe in <DATE>1961</DATE>," <PERSON>Auchard</PERSON> writes, "along with a note that said bake the
pudding and serve with foaming sauce. I think I can figure out the baking
time, the pan and temperature but I don't know how to make the sauce. This was
a popular recipe in the <DATE>1900s</DATE>." She sends the pudding recipe along to see if
it will jog some memories.; RAILROAD PUDDING; 1 egg; 1 cup sugar; 1 tablespoon
butter, melted; 1 1/2 cups flour; 1 teaspoon baking powder; 1/2 cup milk; 1
teaspoon vanilla or lemon extract; Mix ingredients, bake and serve with
foaming sauce.; Calls for help; <PERSON>Billie Schmidt</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION> writes that she
remembers a dish served in <LOCATION>York</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pa.</LOCATION>, that included shrimp cooked in the
shell. "I only remember the shrimp, celery leaf and vinegar ingredients. Can
someone provide the recipe?";   <PERSON>Cheryl Calmis</PERSON>  of <LOCATION>Redwood City</LOCATION> is looking for
a recipe for sweet corn cake such as that served at <LOCATION>El Torito</LOCATION> restaurant.;  
<PERSON>Deloras Giovannetti</PERSON>  of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> would like two recipes: one for a soft, chewy
praline candy, and one for a daffodil cake made with pineapple ("possibly a
1930s recipe," she writes).;   <ORGANIZATION>Marx Parish  of Campbell</ORGANIZATION> also seeks two
recipes: one for preserving fruit in brandy and another for the artichoke
seasoning as prepared and served at the <ORGANIZATION>Chart House</ORGANIZATION> on Maui.;   And <PERSON>Roy A.
Blockinger</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> wonders if there really is a recipe for humble pie.
Could there be?  </TEXT>
