<HEAD>Chances Are That July 4 Firecracker Was Made in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the fireworks being set off to
celebrate American freedom this week were shipped from <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> before
that country's bloody crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators, a
fireworks expert says.
   The Chinese have targeted the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> fireworks market since
relations improved during the <PERSON>Nixon</PERSON> administration and now dominate
the market, said <PERSON>John A. Conkling</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>Maryland</LOCATION> chemist who heads the
<ORGANIZATION>American Pyrotechnics Association</ORGANIZATION>.
   Conkling, who operates a seasonal ``Fireworks Hotline'' in
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, said shipments from <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> had either arrived or were
aboard vessels by the time the disturbances began that led to last
month's bloody crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators. Hundreds,
perhaps thousands, of people were killed.
   ``I think the fact that for the <DATE>past 15 years</DATE> we've celebrated
Independence Day with fireworks coming from a communist country
means there has been an irony quite a while,'' he said. ``It is
heightened by the incidents this year.''
   Most fireworks used by Americans come from overseas, more than
half from <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, he said, adding that the question concerning
possible trade sanctions would be, ``Whom do you punish?''
   In <DATE>1987</DATE>, the latest year for which he had full statistics, <MONEY>50
million pounds</MONEY> of fireworks came to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> directly from
<LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and more than 10 million pounds came from <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> by way of <LOCATION>Hong
Kong</LOCATION> distributors. That left just <MONEY>6 million pounds</MONEY> exported to the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> by the rest of the world, including such former
fireworks-making giants as <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Macao</LOCATION>.
   Most of the fireworks are of the backyard variety _ firecrackers,
Roman candles, skyrockets _ and not the kind seen at public displays.
   <ORGANIZATION>Commerce Department</ORGANIZATION> figures show Chinese shipments of
``explosives and pyrotechnics'' have risen steadily since <DATE>1983</DATE>, when
they were valued at <MONEY>$33.4 million</MONEY>, to <MONEY>$51.2 million</MONEY> in <DATE>1987</DATE>.
   The Chinese, who made ``fire lances'' with a mixture of
saltpeter, sulfur and charcoal as early as the <DATE>12th century</DATE>, now
tailor their products for Americans.
   For instance, the Chinese began making sparklers because
Americans wanted them.
   Many of the fireworks on display at roadside stands still have
distinct oriental imagery: pagodas, blossoms and butterflies.
   A <MONEY>$13</MONEY> package put together by a <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION> company is called the
``Miss Liberty'' assortment. A few of the pieces in it are Chinese,
including one with unintended timeliness: A tiny Chinese-made paper
tank moves on the ground and ``emits flaming pellets.''
   For years, controversy over the Chinese imports has involved
safety rather than questions of politics or human rights in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>.
   Last year, the <ORGANIZATION>Consumer Product Safety Commission</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Customs
Service</ORGANIZATION> seized so many Chinese fireworks for bad labels, short fuses
or gunpowder overloads that the industry had to shut down for a time.
   Conkling was among a group of American experts who toured the
Chinese fireworks provinces last year to work with the makers on
safety standards.
</TEXT>
