<LEADPARA>  PASSING the peanuts has become passe and that bowl of potato chips just
doesn't bowl us over.;    It's time for something new in Super Bowl snacks.
For a change of taste, here's a mixed bag of homemade munchies that offer
variety of flavors and textures that you can't get in a cellophane package.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SNACKS CHEER UP PARTY, EVEN WITHOUT NINERS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Entertaining
Louise Fiszer is founder of Louise's Pantry Cooking School in Menlo Park and
author of "Season to Taste" (Simon &amp; Schuster).  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Crisp Roquefort crackers are so tasty they can be served without a spread.
(Make lots because you can't eat just one.);    Ho-hum canned olives come
alive with flavor and can become addictive when marinated in mustard and
herbs. Packaged won ton skins are transformed to spicy whimsical curled
ribbons when deep fried and accompanied by a chili mint dipping sauce.;    And
for those who can't conceive of football without peanuts, combine them with
raisins and chocolate for a chunky sweet treat.;  CHOCOLATE NUT AND RAISIN
CLUSTERS;  1 pound bittersweet chocolate, cut into small pieces for melting; 
1 cup raisins;  1 cup dry roasted peanuts;   Over low heat or in top of double
boiler, melt chocolate, stirring until smooth. Remove from heat and stir in
raisins and peanuts. Drop by tablespoonfuls onto a sheet of waxed paper. Place
in cool dry place until chocolate clusters are firm. Makes about 36.; (hbox); 
  ROQUEFORT CRACKER CRISPS;  1/2 cup butter, room temperature;  1/2 pound
Roquefort cheese, room temperature;  1 cup flour;  1/2 teaspoon freshly ground
black pepper;   Combine all ingredients until well blended and smooth. Form
into 2 rolls 1 1/2 inches in diameter. Wrap in waxed paper and refrigerate
until firm, at least 3 hours. Slice into 1/4-inch thick. Preheat oven to 400
degrees. Bake on ungreased cookie sheet 10 minutes or until lightly browned.
Remove and store in airtight container. Makes about 36.; (hbox);    CURRIED
WON TON RIBBONS WITH CHILI MINT DIP;  1 package won ton skins;   Oil for deep
frying;  1/2 to 1 teaspoon curry powder;  1/4 teaspoon salt;   Arrange won
tons in stacks of 6 and cut into 3/4-inch strips with serrated pastry wheel.
In medium pan, heat enough oil to deep fry to 375 degrees and fry several
ribbons at a time until golden brown. They will curl up as they cook. Drain on
paper towels and sprinkle with curry and salt.; DIP;  1/2 cup yogurt;  2 green
onions, chopped;  2 green chilies, seeded and chopped;  1 tablespoon brown
sugar;  1/4 cup chopped mint leaves;  3/4 cup chopped fresh coriander leaves; 
 Salt and pepper;   Combine all ingredients until well blended.; (hbox);   
MUSTARD MARINATED; OLIVES;  2 cups water;  1/2 cup white wine vinegar;  1 bay
leaf;  1 tablespoon mustard seed;  1/2 teaspoon salt;  1/2 teaspoon black
peppercorns;  1 tablespoon sugar;  2 16-ounce cans pitted black olives,
drained;  2 tablespoons chopped parsley;   In medium saucepan, bring all
ingredients to a boil except olives and parsley. Simmer, covered 10 minutes.
Remove from heat and place olives in mixture. Allow to cool and then transfer
to jar and place in refrigerator for 24 hours. Drain olives and sprinkle with
parsley. Makes about 4 cups.  </TEXT>
