<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO:; Peanut butter bananarama shake and no-bake granola bars make a
healthy, on-the-run breakfast for adults and kids.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  RECIPE; LIST; FOOD; FAMILY; LIFESTYLE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WAKE up: It's time for breakfast.;    Too busy, you say. Never can eat in the
morning. Got to get the kids up, dog walked, cat fed, coffee made, paper read,
lunches packed, self washed and dressed and out the door. Who has time to eat
breakfast, let alone cook it?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NO TIME FOR BREAKFAST IS NO EXCUSE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     True, weekday mornings are not the time for most of us to whip up pancakes
or even scramble an occasional egg. But aren't you weary of the old
cereal-bagel-toast-juice routine?;    Thought so. Why not rethink the day's
first meal? How about breakfast pizza? A baked apple? A toasted slice of
homemade quick bread with cheese? A made-by-you frozen yogurt pop? A warm
slice of homemade quiche?;    Breakfast fruit;  Imagine the first bite from a
bowl of cold, juicy grapefruit and orange sections, sprinkled with a few
berries and a mango slice or so.;    Impossible? Nah. Not if you're willing to
do a little planning, a little night-before preparation and a little weekend
baking. Then, rely on the microwave and blender to jump-start your mornings.; 
  While you're at all this breakfast revamping, consider starting a family
tradition of <DATE>Saturday</DATE> or <DATE>Sunday</DATE> morning pancakes, waffles or French toast.
Make a double batch and freeze the rest. Put them in one layer on a baking
sheet and freeze until firm; then bag or wrap. You can take out one or more as
you need and microwave them.;    Thoughts for food;  Here are some more ideas
for breakfast. (A few of them are from an article in a <DATE>September 1988</DATE> issue of
1,001 Home Ideas magazine.);    (box) Breakfast pizza: Why not? And who says
pizza has to have tomato sauce? A slice of mozzarella cheese on an English
muffin or pita bread, a sprinkle of oregano, a minute under the broiler and
you're set.;    (box) Bake a breakfast quiche from your favorite recipe, but
substitute Canadian bacon, liquid egg substitute and reduced-fat cheese for
higher-fat ingredients such as bacon or ham, eggs and rich cheese. Cool, slice
into servings, wrap well and freeze. Rewarm in the microwave.;    (box) Top
your favorite toast with sliced tomatoes and a sprinkle of Parmesan cheese.
Broil until bubbly.;    (box) Top a rice cake with cottage cheese and berries
or peanut butter and bananas.;    (box) For quick baked apples, prepare the
night before and refrigerate. Rewarm in the microwave and add a dollop of
vanilla yogurt.;    (box) Yogurt. Need we say more? Try it with a helping of
wheat germ on top. Stir in a spoonful of all-fruit spread. Add a few raisins.;
   (box) Spend a little extra for individual boxes of cereal to toss into a
briefcase or lunch box. Or be more frugal and portion out cereal from a big
box.;    For kid power;  Here are some child-friendly breakfast ideas. They're
easy enough for older kids to do themselves.;    (box) Make fruit and cheese
kebabs: Alternate cubes of cheese and fruit on small wooden skewers, wrap well
and refrigerate overnight.;    (box) Make your own trail mix and pack it into
little plastic bags or containers to eat on the way to school or work.;   
(box) For fun, make miniature muffins instead of regular size. If they're a
few days old, split and toast them, then spread with cream cheese.;    (box)
Remember, chocolate milk is not the worst thing in the world.;    (box) Frost
a banana with peanut butter, roll in crushed cereal, wrap and freeze. Yum.;   
(box) A sandwich for breakfast? Put together a cheese sandwich the night
before and quickly grill it in the morning.;    (box) Scoop yogurt into an ice
cream cone. Add sprinkles of wheat germ or raisins or a dollop of all-fruit
jam.;    (box) Along the same lines, dish up a breakfast parfait or banana
split. Recipes below.;    (box)  A breakfast ice-cream bar? Make them with
yogurt and fruit or fruit juice and fruit. Cold and yummy.;   BREAKFAST POPS; 
 1 8-ounce container yogurt;  1 small sliced banana;  1/2 cup sliced
strawberries or other fruit;   Stir fruit into yogurt, then spoon into paper
or plastic cups. Insert a ice-cream stick (or small plastic spoon) and freeze.
When firm, wrap in foil. Makes 2 small pops.; (hbox);    This recipe, which
goes together in about 5 minutes, is from an old <ORGANIZATION>Southern Living</ORGANIZATION>. Be careful
not to over-mix the batter; it doesn't have to be smooth. A crack in the top
of the loaf is normal; it's also normal for quick breads to look pretty flat,
not domed like yeast breads. (Low-cholesterol cooks could substitute 2 egg
whites for the beaten egg.);    I've also baked this as muffins (they're done
in about 25 minutes). Bread or muffins freeze well.;      APPLESAUCE-PECAN
BREAD;  2 cups all-purpose flour (or 1 1/2 cups flour and 1/2 cup wheat germ);
 1 tablespoon baking powder;  1/2 teaspoon baking soda;  1/2 teaspoon salt; 
3/4 cup sugar;  1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon;  1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg; 
1/2 cup chopped pecans;  1/2 cup raisins;  1 egg, beaten;  1 cup applesauce
(or 1 cup mashed ripe banana or 1 cup canned pumpkin puree);  1/4 cup
vegetable oil;   Combine first 7 ingredients in a large bowl; stir in pecans
and raisins. Make a well in center of dry mixture. Combine egg, applesauce and
oil; add to dry ingredients, stirring just until moistened. Spoon mixture into
a greased and floured loaf pan. Bake at 350 degrees for 40 to 45 minutes or
until a wooden pick inserted in the center comes out clean. Cool in pan 10
minutes; remove from pan, and let cool on a wire rack.; (hbox);    This is
from a baby and toddler cookbook called "Mommy Made (And Daddy, Too)" by
<PERSON>Martha</PERSON> and <PERSON>David Kimmel</PERSON> (<DATE>1990</DATE>, <MONEY>$13.95</MONEY>, Bantam trade paperback). It's good for
grown-ups as well.;  PEANUT BUTTER <LOCATION>BANANARAMA</LOCATION> SHAKE;  1 very ripe banana,
peeled and sliced;  2 tablespoons smooth peanut butter;  1 cup or more milk; 
2 ice cubes (or more);  1 teaspoon honey (optional);   Place all ingredients
in a blender and whirl until smooth. Add more milk if too thick. Serve soon or
banana will start to darken. Makes enough for 1 adult and 1 child or 2
toddlers.; (hbox);   BREAKFAST BANANA SPLIT;  1 small banana, sliced in half
lengthwise;  8 ounce carton vanilla yogurt;  2 tablespoons sliced strawberries
or raspberries;  2 tablespoons blueberries;  2 tablespoons crushed pineapple; 
2 tablespoons granola or chopped nuts;   If you have banana-split dishes, use
them. Otherwise, use a small oblong dish. Place banana halves on sides of
dish, then place yogurt in three scoops down center. Top each scoop with
fruit, then sprinkle with granola or nuts. Serve immediately. Makes 1
serving.;    Note: Try banana split with other flavors of yogurt and your
favorite fruits. How about lemon yogurt and chopped mangoes or peaches?;
(hbox);    These are easy enough for anyone to make. Wrap bars individually
and grab one on the way out the door when you're really in a rush. The recipe
is from <LOCATION>Pillsbury.</LOCATION>;     NO-BAKE GRANOLA BARS;  1/2 cup firmly packed brown
sugar;  1/2 cup light corn syrup; 1 cup peanut butter; 1 teaspoon vanilla; 1
1/2 cups quick-cooking rolled oats; 1 1/2 cups crisp rice cereal; 1 cup
raisins;  1/2 cup coconut;  1/2 cup sunflower seeds; 2 tablespoons sesame
seeds;   In a medium saucepan, combine brown sugar and corn syrup. Bring to a
boil, stirring constantly. Remove from heat. Stir in peanut butter and
vanilla; blend well. Add remaining ingredients and mix well. Press into
ungreased 9-inch-square pan. Cool, then cut into 20 bars.; (hbox);  TROPICAL
SHAKE;  2  tablespoons frozen orange juice concentrate;  1 cup ginger ale or
skim milk;  2 tablespoons non-fat dry milk powder;   Handful of ice cubes; 
1/4 cup canned crushed pineapple;  2 tablespoons coconut;   Blend orange
juice, ginger ale or milk, and dry milk in blender until creamy. Add ice,
pineapple and coconut and blend again. Serve at once.;    Note: You can
substitute frozen pineapple juice concentrate and bananas for orange juice and
pineapple.  </TEXT>
