<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: 'You can't go home every day after a long day at work and make
beef Wellington or salmon en croute.  '  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  HEALTH; FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  MEATLOAF, the quintessential back-to-basics food that was unspeakable during
most of the 1980s, is the perfect comfort food when times are tough.;    It's
inexpensive, simple and requires less time cleaning up in the kitchen than all
those 20- and 30-minute meals that sometimes take several bowls and a couple
of pans. Sure, meatloaf takes an hour or so to cook, but you can watch
television, read the newspaper or even take a catnap while you wait for it to
warm the kitchen and stir your memories.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MEATLOAF: JUST DUMP INTO A BOWL, SQUISH AND
BAKE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Everyone seems to be talking meatloaf these days -- from <PERSON>Jane</PERSON> and <PERSON>Michael
Stern</PERSON>, cookbook authors who have made a career of praising old-fashioned "mom"
food, to <PERSON>Sharon Moore</PERSON>, author of the recently released "Meatloaf" (<PERSON>Clarkson N.
Potter</PERSON>, <MONEY>$10.95</MONEY>).;    <PERSON>Michael Stern</PERSON> says even the name "meatloaf" is so
cloddish that it is disarming and can't help but win our hearts. Even its
preparation spells simpler times.;    "There's no really complicated recipe
for meatloaf," he says. "You just take the ingredients, dump them into a bowl,
squish them together and bake it. . . . Any idiot can make it. That's why it's
so comforting. You don't have to cut it and carve it. It's simple to eat. And
the taste of a classic meatloaf is quite homogenized. There are no
surprises.";    <PERSON>Moore</PERSON> has taken these basic principles and come up with 42
recipes that range from down-home classics like <ORGANIZATION>Granny</ORGANIZATION>'s Meatloaf, made with
ground veal, pork and beef and topped with bacon, to imaginative versions like
the Blue Ribbon Loaf, flavored with Dijon mustard and blue cheese.;    <PERSON>Colleen
Pierre</PERSON>, national spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION>American Dietetic Association</ORGANIZATION>, suggests
grinding your own meat.;    "Normally when you buy ground meat it is a
combination of meat and fat ground together," she says. "If you would buy very
lean pork tenderloin or lean ground beef and grind it yourself, you could cut
the fat considerably.";    If you look for ground chicken or turkey, read the
label carefully, <PERSON>Pierre</PERSON> adds. For example, ground turkey can include a lot of
fatty turkey skin or can be a combination of white and dark meat. Look for
ground turkey breast, the leanest option.;    Even if you make the ingredients
more healthful, the psychological result remains the same as it was when you
came home from school and feasted on the comfort of Mom's meatloaf and mashed
potatoes, <PERSON>Moore</PERSON> says.;    "A lot of us went off to work and stopped cooking,"
she says. "The only time we cooked was during holidays and for fancy gourmet
dinners. "People are now cooking more often and they tend to want to prepare
what Mother made. You can't go home every day after a long day at work and
make beef <LOCATION>Wellington</LOCATION> or salmon en croute."; BLUE RIBBON LOAF;  2 large eggs; 1
tablespoon Dijon mustard;  1/4 cup port;  Salt (if desired) and freshly ground
black pepper to taste; 1 pound ground lean beef or veal; 1 pound ground lean
pork; 3 cups fine dry bread crumbs; 1 cup finely chopped onion;  1/4 pound
blue cheese, crumbled;  Red grapes, optional;   Preheat oven to 350. Beat the
eggs in a mixing bowl; blend in the mustard and port. Stir in the salt and
pepper (salt may not be necessary unless using processed blue cheese). Work in
the veal or beef, pork, bread crumbs and onion and blend thoroughly.;    Place
the mixture on a 24-inch-long piece of wax paper and press it into a
9-by-16-inch rectangle. Sprinkle the blue cheese evenly over the top, leaving
a margin of 1 1/2 inches on all sides. Carefully roll up the rectangle like a
jelly roll, sealing the outside seam and ends by pressing down firmly.;   
Transfer the roll to a buttered or oiled 9-by-5-by-3-inch loaf pan by picking
up the wax paper and inverting it. Bake for 45 minutes to 1 hour, until firm.
Garnish with red grapes, if desired. Makes 6 to 8 servings.; -- From
"Meatloaf"; (hbox);     HERBED AND CRUSTED; TURKEY LOAF; 2 1/2 pounds ground
turkey;  1/4 pound thinly sliced cooked ham, finely chopped; 1 small shallot,
minced; 1 teaspoon salt;  1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper; 2 large
eggs, lightly beaten; 1 cup cooked rice;  1/8 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg;
2 tablespoons minced fresh parsley; 1 tablespoon minced fresh basil or 1
teaspoon dried;  1/2 teaspoon minced fresh sage, or a pinch of dried;  2/3 cup
light cream or half and half; 1 small garlic, bruised; 2 tablespoons plus
additional unsalted butter, softened;  1/2 cup fresh bread crumbs;  Dash hot
pepper sauce;  SAUCE:;  1/2 cup sour cream at room temperature;  Salt and
freshly ground black pepper;   Preheat oven to 350. Combine all the
ingredients through the light cream in a large bowl. Mix thoroughly.;    Rub a
shallow baking dish with butter. Rub the dish with the bruised garlic. Form
the turkey mixture into a loaf in the dish and lightly rub the loaf with
garlic. Mix the 2 tablespoons butter with the bread crumbs in a small bowl
until smooth. Add the hot pepper sauce and spread the crumbs carefully over
the loaf, making sure none fall into the dish. Bake 1 1/2 hours.;    Remove
the drippings (there will be only a small amount) from the dish and transfer
to a bowl. Cover the loaf loosely with foil; let stand 10 minutes. Meanwhile,
stir the sour cream into the drippings and season with salt and pepper to
taste. Serve on the side. Makes 6 to 8 servings.; -- From "As American as
Apple Pie" by <PERSON>Phillip Stephen Schulz</PERSON> (<ORGANIZATION>Simon &amp; Schuster</ORGANIZATION>, <MONEY>$19.95</MONEY>); (hbox);   
The following meatloaf recipe resulted from one of those nights when it was
too cold to go to the store and I was forced to create from what was already
in the pantry and refrigerator.;     CHAR'S STAY-AT-HOME COLD WEATHER
MEATLOAF;   1 pound lean ground beef;  1 pound lean ground pork;  2 eggs,
beaten;  1/4 cup Parmesan cheese;  1/4 cup Italian seasoned bread crumbs;  1
tablespoon sun-dried tomato bits, available in gourmet stores;  2 plum
tomatoes, chopped, and 1 tablespoon juice from canned tomatoes;  1 tablespoon
fresh dill, chopped;  1 carrot, chopped fine;  1 medium yellow onion, chopped
fine;  1/2 teaspoon garlic powder;  1/2 teaspoon onion powder;   Salt and
pepper, to taste;  3 to 4 tablespoons tomato sauce or spaghetti sauce for
topping, optional;   Preheat oven to 375. Combine all the ingredients except
tomato sauce in a large bowl and mix well. Form the meatloaf in an oven-proof
rectangular casserole or a 9-by-5-by-3-inch loaf pan. Bake for 45 minutes to 1
hour until firm. About 15 minutes before the end of cooking, spread tomato or
spaghetti sauce in thin layer on top of meatloaf. Remove from oven and allow
to cool for 10 minutes. Makes 8 servings.;    Note: To minimize fat in the
meatloaf, pour off excess fat two or three times during cooking.;  Add health;
to tradition;  <PERSON>Sharon Moore</PERSON>'s "Meatloaf" book gives advice for adapting some
of the recipes to meet the health concerns of the <DATE>1990s</DATE>:; (box)  Instead of
ground beef or pork, use chicken, turkey, fish, low-fat cheese or tofu.; (box)
 Substitute low-fat bread and crackers, bran, corn bread, cooked rice,
potatoes, pastas or green beans for the bread or bread crumbs.;    (box) If
your doctor has limited your intake of eggs, use two egg whites for each whole
egg called for in the recipe.; (box)  Liquid ingredients could include low-fat
or skim milk, low-fat yogurt, defatted homemade chicken, beef or veal stock or
liquid from cooking vegetables.  </TEXT>
