<DESCRIPT>  CAMP; CHILDREN; FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  These take-along meals; and treats will turn even  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HAPPY TRAILS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  the grumpiest campers; into those raring to go; OATMEAL-RAISIN; BACKPACK
SNACKS; 1 cup sweet butter or margarine, softened; 3/4 cup light brown sugar,
firmly packed; 3/4 cup granulated sugar; 1 large egg; 1 1/2 cups all-purpose
flour; 1 teaspoon baking soda; 1/2 teaspoon salt; 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon;
1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg; 1 1/2 cups rolled oats, uncooked, not
quick-cooking or instant; 1 1/2 cups dark raisins; 2 cups coarsely chopped
walnuts; 1 tablespoon vanilla extract;  Heat oven to 350 degrees. Butter two
cookie sheets.;   In a large bowl, beat butter with electric mixer on high
speed until creamy. Add the brown sugar, granulated sugar, then egg, beating
until light yellow and creamy.;   In small bowl, stir together flour, soda,
salt, cinnamon and nutmeg; stir into butter mixture. Stir in oats, raisins,
walnuts and vanilla. Roll into balls, then in additional granulated sugar, if
desired. Place on cookie sheets, flattening cookies slightly. Bake 10 minutes
or until lightly browned. Let stand 2 minutes on cookie sheet; remove to wire
rack to cool. Store in tightly sealed container.;   Makes about 9 dozen 2-inch
cookies.;  FRESH CATCH; 1 cup pecans or walnuts; 1/2 cup all-purpose flour;
1/4 cup yellow cornmeal; 1 teaspoon baking powder;  Salt and pepper; 2 whole
brook trout, about 12 ounces each, cleaned, heads and tails left on; 1/2 cup
milk or water; 6 tablespoons peanut or other vegetable oil;  Fresh lemon
slices;  Place pecans, flour, cornmeal and baking powder in food processor;
process until fine. Place mixture in well-sealed food container and take to
campsite.;   About 20 minutes before serving, salt and pepper each trout or
other catch of the day. Dip in milk, then dredge the outsides plus the inside
cavities of the fish with pecan mixture, pressing lightly to coat well. Heat
oil in large skillet over medium-high heat. Saute the fish about 8 minutes,
until crisp and golden, turning once. Garnish with lemon slices. Makes 2
servings.;  FRUIT LEATHER; 2 cups fruit; 2 teaspoons lemon juice; 1/2 cup corn
syrup or honey;  Select ripe or slightly overripe fruit. Wash in cool water;
remove peel, seeds and stem. Cut fruit into chunks. Puree fruit until smooth.;
  Add lemon juice and sweetener.;   Line a 13-by-15-inch cookie pan with edges
with plastic wrap, being sure to smooth out wrinkles. Do not use waxed paper
or aluminum foil. Pour puree into a single large sheet. Spread puree evenly,
about 1/8-inch thick. Avoid pouring puree too close to the edge of the cookie
sheet.;   Approximate drying times are: 6 to 8 hours in a dehydrator, up to 18
hours in a 140-degree oven and 1 to 2 days in the sun. Test for dryness by
touching center of leather; no indention should be evident. While warm, peel
from plastic and roll, allow to cool and rewrap the roll in plastic.;   Fruit
leather will keep up to 1 month at room temperature; up to 1 year wrapped
tightly and frozen.;  GRANOLA BARS; 4 1/2 cups rolled oats; 1/2 teaspoon salt;
2 teaspoons vanilla; 1/2 cup oil; 1/2 cup honey; 2 tablespoons molasses; 1/2
cup finely chopped walnuts; 1/2 cup finely chopped dried fruit;  Put all
ingredients into a bowl and mix well with hands. Place mixture into oiled
9-by-13-inch baking dish. Press down evenly and firmly with metal spatula.
Bake at 400 degrees for 15 minutes. Reverse dish and bake an additional 5
minutes. Watch carefully. Cool completely before cutting. Makes 30 bars.;
CAMPER'S CLASSIC; JERKY MARINADE; 1 teaspoon salt; 1 teaspoon pepper; 3
tablespoons brown sugar; 1/4 cup Worcestershire sauce; 1/4 cup tamari or soy
sauce; 1 tablespoon liquid smoke; 2 pounds round or flank steak or other
low-fat cut of meat, sliced (see note);  In a bowl, mix together marinade
ingredients. Pour over meat slices; thoroughly wet all sides of meat with
marinade and layer in the marinating dish.;   Cover tightly and marinate in
refrigerator overnight or from 6 to 12 hours. For best results rotate meat
layers every few hours until ready to dry.;   To dry: After marinating jerky,
dry in your dehydrator at 140 to 160 degrees for the first 4 hours, then you
may reduce heat to 130 degrees until dry. For oven drying, heat should be 140
to 160 degrees for about 8 hours, then lower to 130 degrees till dry. You can
also dry jerky in the oven at a constant temperature of 150 degrees for 10
hours, but you'll get better results with the other two methods. Makes about
1/2 pound jerky.;   Note: You may want to partially freeze the meat first to
make cutting easier. Cut strips 3 inches or longer by about 1-inch wide and
1/4-inch thick. Cut across the grain for more tender jerky, with the grain for
tougher, chewy strips. Some people like to cut jerky in paper-thin sheets.;
CURRIED LENTIL SOUP BASE; 3 to 4 cups water; 2 14 1/2-ounce cans chicken
broth; 2 cups lentils; 1 fresh onion, diced; 3 cloves garlic,minced; 1
tablespoon grated ginger; 4 teaspoon curry powder; 2 teaspoon ground
coriander; 1/4 teaspoon red pepper flakes; 1 tablespoon olive oil;  At home:
Bring water, chicken broth and lentils to boil, reduce heat, and cover. Simmer
on low heat 20 to 45 minutes or until lentils are cooked through. Keep
watching and add more water if too thick, but as little as possible. Cook
onion, garlic, ginger, curry, coriander, and pepper in oil over medium heat 7
minutes. Stir spice mixture into lentils. Cover. Cook over medium-low heat 20
minutes. Cook down to thick paste, taking care not to burn.;   Spread on
plastic sheets in a dehydrator. Dry at 145 degrees until dehydrated, about 6
hours. Or, dry in an oven on a cookie sheet at 130-150 degrees. (Turn oven on
lowest setting with door propped open. Use an oven thermometer to make sure
oven maintains steady temperature. Rotate food and remove as it becomes dry.)
Repackage and store in refrigerator until ready to use.;   In Camp: Rehydrate
with boiling water until desired thickness.;   -- This and the following two;
recipes from "Wilderness; Cuisine" by <PERSON>Carole Latimer</PERSON>; (<ORGANIZATION>Wilderness Press</ORGANIZATION>,
<DATE>1991</DATE>); BUTTERMILK CORNBREAD; 1 cup yellow cornmeal; 1/2 cup whole wheat flour;
1/2 cup white flour; 1 tablespoon baking powder; 1/4 cup powdered egg; 4
tablespoons powdered buttermilk or 1/4 cup dry milk; 1/4 cup sugar; 1/3 cup
safflower oil; 1 1/4  cup water;  At home: Combine dry ingredients in a
plastic bag. Add oil to main supply.;   In camp: Combine all ingredients and
mix well. Pour into oiled 3-quart pot and steam for 30 to 45 minutes or pour
into a Banks Frybake Pan and bake for 20 to 30 minutes. Makes 8 to 10
servings.;   -- This and the following; three recipes are from <ORGANIZATION>Mercury; News
Wire Services</ORGANIZATION>  </TEXT>
