<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE; HOLIDAY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE candy corn and candy wrappers of Halloween have barely faded from sight
and yet my mind races to the preparations for the holiday season ahead.;   One
way I can got a handle on this time of year is to make foods that are great
for storing and using in a holiday menu or giving as gifts that will be
happily received. Glittering Walnuts will disappear like magic when served as
a nibble with a glass of sherry or champagne. Pack them in an airtight faceted
apothecary jar, tie a plaid ribbon around the neck and you have a fabulous
gift.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RECIPES SPRUCE UP THANKSGIVING MENU, MAKE TASTY
GIFTS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Entertaining; Louise Fiszer is founder of Louise's Pantry Cooking School in
Menlo Park and author of "Season to Taste" (Simon &amp; Schuster).  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Cranberry-Apple Relish is a snap to make in the food processor. Serve at
your own Thanksgiving table for a special turkey condiment. For gift giving,
pack in French jelly jars with plastic snap-on lids. Cut a six-inch circle
from holiday wrapping paper and fit over top and secure with rubber band. Tie
ribbon around rubber band.;   A flavorful herb- or spice-infused mustard is
great for those sandwiches made from holiday leftover turkey and ham. Two jars
packed in a lined wicker basket make an attractive and tasty gift.; GLITTERING
SPICED; WALNUTS; 1 star anise pod, ground; 1/2 teaspoon coriander seed,
ground; 1/2 teaspoon Szechuan peppercorns, ground; 1/4 teaspoon fennel seed,
ground; 1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon; 1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper; 1 pound
walnut halves; 1/2 cup granulated sugar; Vegetable oil for deep-frying; Salt
to taste;  In small bowl combine spices and set aside. Boil walnuts in enough
water to cover for 1 minute. Pour into colander and rinse under hot water.
Toss well with sugar. Heat oil to 350 degrees. Deep-fry in 2 batches until
golden brown, about 3 minutes. Spread on cookie sheets to cool and then blot
in paper toweling. Place in bowl and toss with spice mixture. Taste for salt.
Pack in an air tight container at room temperature. Makes 4 cups.; (hbox);  
CRANBERRY APPLE RELISH; 1 orange, quartered and seeded; 1 lime, quartered and
seeded; 1 large <PERSON>Granny Smith</PERSON> apple, cored and quartered; 1 12-ounce package of
cranberries; 1/2 cup sugar; 1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon; 1/4 cup apple brandy
or applejack;  Place all ingredients in food processor and chop until fine.
Store in airtight containers in refrigerator. Makes about 3 cups.; (hbox);   
BASIC HOMEMADE MUSTARD; 1/4 cup mustard seed; 1/4 cup dry mustard; 1/2 cup hot
water; 1/2 cup white wine or flavored vinegar; 1 teaspoon salt; 1 teaspoon
honey;  In small bowl, combine mustard seed, dry mustard and water. Let sit,
uncovered, about 2 hours. Combine in food processor with remaining ingredients
to desired consistency. Pour into clean jars, cover tightly and refrigerate.
Makes 1 cup.;   Coriander Mint Mustard: Add 1 tablespoon chopped fresh mint
leaves and 2 teaspoons ground coriander seed to basic recipe.;  
Tarragon-Shallot Mustard: Add 1 tablespoon pureed shallot and 1 tablespoon
chopped fresh tarragon leaves to basic recipe.;   Red Pepper Honey Mustard:
Using basic recipe, increase honey to 2 tablespoons and stir in 1 teaspoon red
pepper flakes.  </TEXT>
