<LEADPARA>  Bottled horseradish can do more than add zip to a juicy slice of prime rib.
Here are some other tips on using the condiment:;  (check) Add a teaspoon to
hollandaise sauce and serve on steak, salmon or asparagus.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOT STUFF
A PIQUANT PART OF PASSOVER,
HORSERADISH GOES GREAT WITH PRIME
RIB OR PUTS KICK IN COCKTAIL SAUCE.
NOW LET YOUR IMAGINATION TAKE OVER.  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week
See related article this page  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   (check) Mix a teaspoon into melted preserves and brush on ham or roast beef
as a glaze.;  (check) Blend a teaspoon into 3 ounces of cream cheese and
spread on thinly sliced roast beef, turkey or smoked salmon. Roll and slice
into bite-sized appetizers.;  (check) Add a teaspoon to meat loaf, meatball or
hamburger mixtures.;  (check) Stir into Bloody Marys.;  (check) Blend a
teaspoon into a stick of softened butter and use as a spread for bread, rolls
or baked potatoes.;  (check) Fold a teaspoon into a spinach souffle mixture.; 
(check) Stir a teaspoon into a cup of sour cream and use to make potato salad,
coleslaw or Waldorf salad.;  (check) Beat a teaspoon into eggs before
scrambling.;  COCKTAIL SAUCE;  1 1/2 cups ketchup;  1 tablespoon lemon juice; 
1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce;  2 tablespoons horseradish sauce;  1 1/2
teaspoons sugar;  1/4 teaspoon salt;  1/8 teaspoon hot pepper sauce;  1/8
teaspoon pepper;   Combine all ingredients; chill. Makes 1 3/4 cups.;    --
From "Southern Seafood; Classics" by the <LOCATION>Southeastern</LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION>Fisheries Association</ORGANIZATION>; 
FRESH BEET HORSERADISH;  1 cup grated, peeled fresh horseradish;  1 small
beet, cooked, peeled and grated;  2 tablespoons white vinegar;  1 teaspoon
sugar;   Combine all ingredients in a small bowl and stir well. Cover and
refrigerate. Makes 1 cup. This will keep for about 2 weeks.;    -- From "The
New Basics; Cookbook" by <PERSON>Julee Rosso</PERSON>; and <PERSON>Sheila Lukins</PERSON>;  FLOUNDER AND
HORSERADISH SAUCE;  2 cups water;  4 onion slices;  1 carrot, sliced;  2
sprigs parsley;  1 bay leaf;  1 teaspoon salt;  1 1/2 pounds flounder fillets
or other firm white fish;  1 tablespoon margarine;  4 teaspoons flour;  2
tablespoons horseradish;   Combine water, onion, carrot, parsley, bay leaf and
salt. Simmer 10 minutes. Roll up fillets, secure with toothpicks and place in
stock. Simmer 10 to 12 minutes or until fish turns white and flakes easily.
Remove from liquid. Reserve 1 cup of stock (add water if needed). Melt
margarine and stir in flour until well blended. Gradually add reserved fish
stock, stirring constantly. Simmer 10 minutes to thicken. Remove from heat and
stir in horseradish. Serve with fish. Makes 4 servings.;  CROISSANT
SANDWICHES;  1 3-ounce package cream cheese with chives, softened;  1 teaspoon
prepared horseradish;  1/2 teaspoon chopped garlic;  4 medium croissants;  4
1-ounce slices cooked ham;  1/2 medium cucumber, thinly sliced;   Combine
softened cream cheese, horseradish and garlic. Spread on croissants, add ham
and cucumber slices. Makes 4 servings.;  <LOCATION>CALIFORNIA</LOCATION> BURGERS;  1 pound ground
beef;  2 tablespoons cocktail sauce;  1 tablespoon prepared mustard;  2
tablespoons prepared horseradish;  1/2 cup toasted bread crumbs;   Mix all
ingredients thoroughly. Shape into 4 patties. For rare burgers, broil 3
minutes on each side; for well done, broil 3 to 5 minutes longer. Serve on
toasted rolls, with lettuce and tomato slices if desired. Makes 4 servings.; 
DEVILED BEEF ROAST; ON THE GRILL;  1 beef eye-round roast (3 1/2 to 4 pounds);
 1/2 cup horseradish;  1/4 cup mustard;  2 to 3 cups coarse (kosher) salt;  
Pat beef dry with paper toweling; combine horseradish and mustard and cover
entire surface of beef with mixture. Cover horseradish/mustard layer with
coarse salt; no meat should be visible. Place beef in disposable foil roasting
pan; place pan on grill rack over hot coals. Cover grill; cook until
instant-registering meat thermometer, inserted into center of beef, registers
135-145 degrees, 50 to 60 minutes. Crack salt casing; remove and discard. Cut
beef into thin slices. Makes 8 servings.;  LEEK SALAD;  8 firm fresh leeks, 1
inch in diameter;  1/4 cup sour cream;  1/4 cup cider vinegar;  1/2 teaspoon
Dusseldorf-style prepared mustard or other hot prepared mustard with fresh
horseradish;  1 teaspoon prepared horseradish;   Salt and pepper to taste;  
Cut off roots, strip away tough outer leaves and remove tops. Halve lengthwise
and cut into 2- to 3-inch pieces. Wash under cold running water to remove
sand. Cook in boiling water 15 to 20 minutes until crisp-tender. Drain.;   
Combine 1/4 cup cooking liquid with next 5 ingredients. Beat with whisk or
spoon until well blended. Pour over leeks. Chill one hour or longer. Makes 4
servings.  </TEXT>
