<LEADPARA>  READER Lorie Mascar of San Jose has hit the jackpot. Mascar requested two
recipes: one for a thick teriyaki sauce; another for lemon bars made with a
cake mix and cream cheese. It didn't take long for the recipes to roll in.;  
"I've cooked Oriental food all my life," writes Donna Fanning  of San Jose.
"Teriyaki is a personal thing. While the basis stays pretty much the same,
there can be many variations. I don't thicken my sauce, but the sauce can be
thickened easily with these directions."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  READER STRIKES IT RICH WITH RECIPES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Readers' Exchange  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  TERIYAKI; 3/4 cup soy sauce; 3/4 cup white sugar; 2 cloves garlic, pressed or
minced; 1 1-inch piece of ginger root, peeled, sliced length-wise then sliced
into slivers; Peel grated from 1 lemon; <LOCATION>Cornstarch</LOCATION>; Water;  Put soy sauce;
sugar, garlic, ginger and lemon peel in a non-aluminum saucepan and bring to a
boil. Be careful not to let it boil over. Turn down heat and simmer for 8
minutes. In a bowl, combine a couple of tablespoons cornstarch with about a
1/2 cup cold water. Mixture should look milky. With the sauce at a high
simmer, dribble in the cornstarch, a little at a time, from a gravy ladle
while stirring the mixture constantly with a wooden spoon until you reach the
consistency you desire. Let it simmer a minute or two more before removing it
from the heat.; (hbox);   <PERSON>Trish Seaman</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION> sends this sauce recipe.
It can be stored for several months in the refrigerator, she says.; TOMI'S
TERIYAKI SAUCE; 1 1/2 cups soy sauce; 1 1/2  cups brown sugar; 4 tablespoons
ketchup; 2 tablespoons mirin, Japanese wine; 1/4 teaspoon <ORGANIZATION>Lawry</ORGANIZATION>'s seasoning
salt; 1/4 teaspoon pepper; 5 to 6 peeled cloves of garlic; 1 teaspoon MSG
(optional); 1/8 teaspoon onion powder;  Mix all ingredients together in
saucepan. Stir and heat just to a simmer. Do not boil. Remove from heat and
cool.; A bit of lemon; Here are a few versions of lemon bars for Mascar.
<PERSON>Billie Schmitz</PERSON>  of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Phyllis Marsh</PERSON>  of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> contributed this
version.; LEMON CHEESE-BARS; 1 package yellow cake mix, with pudding added; 2
eggs, divided; 1/3 cup vegetable oil; 1 8-ounce package cream cheese,
softened; 1/3 cup sugar; 1 teaspoon lemon juice;  Mix cake mix, 1 egg and
vegetable oil until crumbly. Reserve 1 cup of the mixture. Pat remaining
mixture in a 13-by-9-by-2-inch pan. Bake 15 minutes at 350 degrees. Beat cream
cheese, sugar, lemon juice and 1 egg until smooth. Spread over baked layer.
Sprinkle with reserved cake mixture and bake 15 minutes longer. Cool and cut
into bars.; (hbox);   This quick and simple version is from <PERSON>Elaine Hoger</PERSON>  of
Saratoga.; LEMON BARS; 1 one step angel food cake mix; 1 can lemon pie
filling; 1 can cream cheese frosting;  Mix cake mix and lemon pie filling
together and spread in a 10-by-15-inch jelly-roll pan that has been well
greased and floured. Bake at 350 degrees for 20 minutes. Cool and frost with
cream cheese frosting. Cut into bars.; (hbox);   <PERSON>Marie Mitchell</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>
printed a big "Yummy!" at the top of her recipe. It doesn't use a cake mix or
cream cheese but it does look yummy.; LEMON BARS; 1 cup butter; 1/2 cup
powdered sugar; 1/4 teaspoon salt; 2 1/4 cups flour, divided; 2 eggs; 2 cups
granulated sugar; 1/4 cup lemon juice; 1 teaspoon grated lemon rind;  Cream
butter, powdered sugar and salt. Stir in 2 cups flour. Press mixture over
bottom of 9- by-13-inch pan. Bake at 325 degrees for 18 to 20 minutes. Do not
overbake. Beat eggs; add granulated sugar and remaining 1/4 cup flour, lemon
juice and rind. Spread over baked mixture. Continue baking for 23 to 25
minutes with additional powdered sugar sprinkled on top, if desired.; Calls
for help; "Recently, I purchased some cinnamon cookies in Mendocino," writes
<PERSON>Joyce Kiefer</PERSON>  of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION>. "I would like to make similar cookies for
<DATE>Christmas</DATE>. They were drop cookies with the cinnamon inside the dough but they
were not snickerdoodles.";   <PERSON>Annette McSheffrey</PERSON>  of <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION> wants a recipe
for a waffle mix that will keep for several days in the refrigerator.;   <PERSON>Betty
Mitre</PERSON>  of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> is looking for a recipe for Pumpkin-Apple Pie. She was told
it had pumpkin filling on the top and apple filling on the bottom and was
delicious.  </TEXT>
