<LEADPARA>  DECK THE halls? Ha!;   This year, money is so tight that most of us will be
lucky to deck a mantel.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ENTERTAINING ON TIGHT BUDGET? THESE APPETIZERS ARE
ASTOUNDINGLY CHEAP  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related article on page 1G of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Obviously, beluga caviar and lobster puffs are out of the question for the
annual holiday hoedown. But don't reach for the Spam and saltines just yet.
There are other low-cost options.;   Start with about 30 friends and add a
Mexican fondue with tortilla chips. Save some of the chips for a spicy, hot
black bean dip.;   Throw in an elegant salmon spread and a robust potted
cheese spread flavored with beer. Round things out with a spicy Asian peanut
dunk for chicken wings and an unusual African-inspired curry dip with sweet
potato fries.;   The cost: About <MONEY>$40.</MONEY>;   The quantities the recipes make will
serve about 30. If you invite more or fewer people, use the rules of thumb
suggested by <PERSON>Susan Wyler</PERSON> in her book, "Cooking for a Crowd." Offer at least
five hors d'oeuvres at a cocktail party and plan on two to three tidbits and
about 1/4 cup of spread per guest.; OVEN-BAKED WINGS WITH SPICY PEANUT DIP; 3
garlic cloves, chopped; 1 cup peanut butter; 2 tablespoon sugar; 1 piece ( 1/2
inch) fresh ginger, peeled and minced; 1/2 jalapeno, chopped; 1/2 cup water; 2
tablespoon soy sauce; 1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice; 2 tablespoon chopped
fresh cilantro; 2 tablespoon Asian sesame oil; 4 1/2 pounds chicken wing
drumettes (about 60 pieces);  In a blender or food processor, combine garlic,
peanut butter, sugar, ginger and jalapeno. Blend well. Add water and soy
sauce, and when well mixed, add lemon juice, cilantro and sesame oil. Makes
about 1 3/4 cups. Immediately before serving, place wings in a single layer on
jelly roll pans (baking sheets with sides). Bake at 400 degrees for 20 to 30
minutes, depending on size of chicken pieces. Serve warm, with peanut dip for
dunking.; -- "From Pantry to Table" by <PERSON>Marlena Spieler</PERSON>; (hbox); BLACK BEAN
NACHO DIP; 1 onion, chopped; 2 garlic cloves, chopped; 2 tablespoon olive oil;
2 teaspoon chili powder; 2 cans (15 ounces each) black beans; Salt, cayenne
pepper to taste; 10 ounces <PERSON>Monterey Jack</PERSON> cheese, sliced thin; 1 teaspoon cumin
seeds; 3 tablespoon chopped fresh cilantro; 2 chopped ripe tomatoes; 2
tablespoon pickled jalapeno pepper slices; Sour cream; Corn tortilla chips; 
Saute onion and garlic in olive oil until softened, then sprinkle with chili
powder and cook a minute longer. Drain liquid from one can of black beans and
add beans to pan. Add second can, undrained. Cook down to a thickened mixture,
mashing the beans slightly as they cook so mixture is partly smooth, partly
chunky. Season to taste with salt and cayenne.;   Spoon bean mixture into a
glass pie pan or rustic ceramic casserole. Recipe can be made ahead to this
point and refrigerated. When ready to serve, top beans with sliced cheese and
sprinkle with cumin seeds. Bake at 450 degrees for about 10 minutes, until
cheese melts and lightly browns. Serve immediately, garnished with cilantro,
tomatoes, jalapeno slices and sour cream. Scoop up with tortilla chips. Makes
about 2 cups.; -- Adapted from "From Pantry to Table"; (hbox); SALMON SPREAD;
7 ounces cooked salmon; 8 ounces cream cheese, softened; 1 tablespoon lemon
juice; 1 tablespoon grated onion; 1 teaspoon horseradish; 1/4 teaspoon liquid
smoke; 1/2 cup chopped walnuts; 3 tablespoon chopped parsley;  Combine salmon,
cream cheese, lemon juice, onion, horseradish and liquid smoke in a food
processor or blender. Process until smooth. Stir in chopped nuts and parsley.
Transfer to a crock. Refrigerate until ready to serve. Serve with crackers.
Makes 2 cups.; -- From "The <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> Classic" by the Junior League of <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION>;
(hbox); SWEET POTATO FRIES WITH CURRIED MAYONNAISE DIP; 2/3 cup mayonnaise;
1/3 cup plain yogurt; 1 tablespoon curry powder; 1 teaspoon ground ginger; 1/2
teaspoon tumeric powder; 1/2 teaspoon chili powder; 1/2 teaspoon paprika,
preferably sweet Hungarian; 1/4 teaspoon salt; 4 large yams; Vegetable oil;
Salt;  In a small bowl, stir together the mayonnaise and yogurt. Stir in
spices and salt. Cover and refrigerate at least 1 hour or overnight. Makes 1
cup. Immediately before serving, scrub potatoes and cut lengthwise into
quarter- to half-inch slices. Cut slices into french-fry shapes. Place on
baking sheets and drizzle with oil, tossing to coat. Spread in a single layer
and season lightly with salt. Bake at 400 degrees for 20 to 25 minutes, or
until cooked through. Serve with curry dip.; -- From "Kwanzaa: An
African-American Celebration of Culture and Cooking" by <PERSON>Eric V. Copage</PERSON>;
(hbox); ULTIMATE CHILI CON QUESO; 2 cups chopped, canned green chilies; 1
pound sharp Cheddar cheese, grated; 1 pound <PERSON>Monterey Jack</PERSON> cheese; 1 cup
whipping cream; 4 cloves garlic, minced; 1 bunch cilantro, minced; 1 teaspoon
ground cumin; 1 teaspoon oregano; 4 cups peeled, seeded, chopped tomatoes,
canned or fresh; 1 8-ounce can pitted black olives, drained and chopped; 6
minced green onions; Tortilla chips;   Combine all ingredients except chips in
a large saucepan. Stir over medium-low heat until cheeses melt. Can be
prepared up to three days in advance, refrigerated, and reheated. Serve in a
fondue pot with tortilla chips.; -- From "Fast and Fabulous Dinner Parties" by
<PERSON>Michele Braden</PERSON>; (hbox); POTTED CHEESE AND BEER SPREAD; 3/4 pound Cheddar
cheese; 1 teaspoon dry mustard; 2/3 cup smooth, flavorful beer; 1/2 cup (1
stick) unsalted butter, slightly softened; 1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce;
Generous grind of white pepper; Pinch or two of cayenne pepper; Salt, if
needed;  Grate cheese and place in bowl. Add dry mustard and beer. Stir
mixture, press cheese down until it is covered by the beer, cover the bowl and
let stand overnight to soften. Place butter in a food processor and beat
briefly until creamy. Add beer-cheese mixture, Worcestershire sauce, white
pepper and cayenne. Process until smooth, scraping bowl once or twice. Season
with salt, if desired.;   Pack into crocks or small bowls. Smooth tops, cover
and refrigerate for up to two weeks. Serve at room temperature with crackers.
Makes 2 2/3 cups.;   -- From "Fancy Pantry" by <PERSON>Helen Witty</PERSON>  </TEXT>
