<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DAILY GRIND
IN THE QUEST FOR THE ZEST, AMERICANS ARE
GRINDING FRESH BLACK PEPPER INTO A VARIETY
OF FOODS -- EVEN DESSERTS.  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   1 tablespoon unsalted butter;  1 1/2 -2 pints strawberries, quartered,
hulled;   Balsamic vinegar;   Black peppercorns in a pepper mill;   Melt
butter in warm skillet. Add strawberries when butter is melted and hot and
toss for about 1 minute. Don't let them get too soft, just warm. Remove from
heat, add a splash of balsamic vinegar and grind fresh pepper on top to taste.
Serves 4.;    -- Chef <PERSON>Charles Weber</PERSON>,; La Tour, <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>; PEPPER CAKE WITH
PUMPKIN AND PRUNES;  1 1/2 cups sifted flour;  1 teaspoon each: baking powder,
cinnamon, ground ginger;  1/2 teaspoon nutmeg;  1/4 teaspoon each: cloves,
salt;  6 ounces (1 cup) soft, moist pitted prunes;  3 ounces preserved stem
ginger in syrup, diced ( 1/3 cup), see note;  4 ounces (generous 1 cup)
walnuts;  1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, softened;  1 teaspoon black
pepper, ground fine;  1/2 cup each: packed light brown sugar, granulated
sugar;  2 large eggs;  1 cup canned solid-pack pumpkin;   Put rack in lower
third of oven. Heat oven to 325 degrees. Butter an 8-cup capacity loaf pan
(such as 10 1/4-by-3 3/4-by-3 1/4 inches). Dust it lightly with flour and tap
out the excess. Sift together the flour, baking powder, cinnamon, ground
ginger, nutmeg, cloves and salt. Cut prunes into 1/4-inch slices. Break nuts
into coarse chunks.;    Beat butter in large mixer bowl until soft. Add black
pepper and both sugars and beat to mix well. Beat in eggs, then the pumpkin
mixture may look curdled; that's OK. Beat in prunes, preserved ginger and
walnuts. Then, with mixer on low speed, add sifted dry ingredients and beat
only until incorporated. Transfer to prepared pan and smooth top. Bake until
cake tester comes out dry, about 1 hour, 40 minutes. Cool in pan 15 minutes,
then invert onto wire rack. Leave cake upside down and cool on rack before
slicing. Yield: 20 slices.;    Note: Preserved stem ginger in syrup is
available at specialty food markets, and some large supermarkets.;    --
Adapted from "<LOCATION>Maida</LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION>Heatter</ORGANIZATION>'s Best Dessert; Book Ever"; POACHED PEARS; WITH;
PEPPER;  4 -6 firm, ripe pears;  2 tablespoons lemon juice;  4 teaspoons whole
black peppercorns;  3 cups cranberry-apple juice;  1/4 cup sugar;  1/2
teaspoon vanilla extract;   Cracked black pepper;   Peel and core pears,
leaving stem intact. Place in a large bowl containing water to cover and 1
tablespoon of the lemon juice. Tie peppercorns in a double thickness of
cheesecloth. Place in a large, deep non-aluminum saucepan with remaining 1
tablespoon lemon juice, cranberry-apple juice and sugar. Heat to a boil, then
cook 1 minute. Drain pears and add to boiling liquid. Reduce heat and simmer,
uncovered, turning occasionally, until pears are tender. Cooking time will
vary from 5 to 8 minutes, depending on how ripe pears are.;    Transfer pears
with their liquid to large bowl and cool slightly. Add vanilla. Cover and
refrigerate at least 2 hours. Remove from refrigerator about 1 hour before
serving. Serve pears with some of the liquid and sprinkle with cracked black
pepper. Yield: 4-6 servings.;    -- From the <ORGANIZATION>Spice Trade; Association</ORGANIZATION>; PEPPER
PASTA;  1 package (12 ounces) black pepper pasta (see note);  2-3 tablespoons
extra-virgin olive oil;  1 clove garlic, minced;  1/4 cup freshly grated
Parmesan or Romano cheese;   Salt to taste;   Chopped parsley or fresh
cilantro for garnish;   Cook pasta in large saucepan according to package
directions. Drain. Heat olive oil in same saucepan until warm; add garlic.
Cook and stir 1 minute (do not allow garlic to brown). Stir in pasta; toss
well to mix. Stir in cheese and salt. Sprinkle with parsley. Serve
immediately. Yield: 4 servings.;    Note: Black pepper pasta is sold at
specialty food markets and supermarkets.; PEPPER AND BLACK FIG; GINGER CAKE; 
8 ounces black mission figs;  4 ounces crystallized ginger;  1 1/2 cups sifted
unbleached flour;  1/2 cup sifted whole wheat flour;  1 teaspoon baking
powder;  1/2 teaspoon salt;  2 teaspoons ground ginger;  2 teaspoons cinnamon;
 1/2 teaspoon nutmeg;  1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper, ground fine;  1
tablespoon cocoa powder;  4 ounces unsalted butter;  2 teaspoons vanilla
extract;  3/4 packed cup light brown sugar;  3 large eggs;  1/4 cup milk;  
Grated rind of 1 orange;  6 ounces walnuts pieces;    Adjust rack one-third
from bottom of oven. Preheat to 350. Butter 8-cup loaf pan. Dust with fine
bread crumbs. Cut figs in 1/4-inch slices. Cut crystallized ginger in 1/4-inch
pieces. Sift together flours, baking powder, salt, ginger, cinnamon, nutmeg,
pepper and cocoa. In large bowl of an electric mixer, beat butter until soft.
Add vanilla and sugar and beat until well-mixed. Beat in eggs, one at a time.
On low speed, add half sifted dry ingredients. Beat in milk and remaining dry
ingredients. Stir in orange rind, figs, ginger and nuts. Pour into pan and
smooth top.;    Bake 80 minutes until cake tester comes out clean. Cool cake
in pan 15 minutes. Remove. Put on a rack to cool. Yields 12-16 slices.;    --
From "<PERSON>Maida Heatter</PERSON>'s; Best Dessert Book Ever"; STEAK AU POIVRE;  2
1-inch-thick strip or club steaks, well trimmed;  1 tablespoon peppercorns,
coarsely crushed;  2 teaspoons salt;  1/4 cup butter;  1 teaspoon
Worcestershire sauce;  2 tablespoons lemon juice;  2 ounces Cognac;   Press
peppercorns into both sides of the steaks with the heel your palm. Sprinkle
the bottom of a skillet with the salt. Put over high heat. When salt begins to
brown, add steaks and brown, uncovered. Reduce to medium and turn steaks. Cook
to desired doneness. Heat butter, Worcestershire sauce and lemon juice in a
separate pan. Remove steaks and pour butter mixture over steaks. Pour Cognac
over and flambe. Serves 2.;    -- From "Joy of Cooking" by <PERSON>Irma S. Rombauer</PERSON>
and <PERSON>Marion Rombauer Becker</PERSON> (<ORGANIZATION>New American Library</ORGANIZATION>)  </TEXT>
