<LEADPARA>  GORGONZOLA WITH BRANDY 4ounces Gorgonzola cheese, at room temperature;  3
ounces cream cheese, at room temperature;  2 tablespoons brandy  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ARISTOCRATS
NOBLES AND COMMONERS ALIKE HAVE ACQUIRED
A TASTE FOR THE DISTINCTIVE FLAVOR OF BLUE-VEINED
CHEESES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   1 tablespoon milk or cream, as needed;   Mix cheeses in small bowl. Add
brandy; mix again. If necessary, thin with milk. Store in refrigerator but
bring to room temperature before serving. Serve with crackers or on iced
cucumber slices. Makes 1 cup.; SHARP ROQUEFORT SALAD DRESSING;  2/3 cup salad
oil;  1/4 cup wine vinegar;  1 bay leaf, crumbled;  1 1/2  ounces crumbled
Roquefort cheese;  1 tablespoon grated onion;   Combine oil, vinegar, bay
leaf, cheese and onion in a jar with a tight-fitting lid. Shake until blended.
Toss dressing with seafood and vegetable salads just before serving. Makes 1
1/4 cups.; STILTON SAUCE;  2 ounces Stilton or other blue-veined cheese;  1
cup heavy cream or half-and-half;  1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice;   Pinch of
cayenne pepper;   Mash cheese to a paste with fork. Work in cream. If
preferred, use small food processor to blend cheese and cream. Add lemon juice
and pepper. Makes 1 cup. Excellent with cold fish, chicken or meat. Also can
be served on the side with club and hamburger sandwiches.;    -- Both recipes
from "Super; Meals from Supermarkets"; by <PERSON>Joe Famularo</PERSON>; BLUE CHEESE TOASTS;  3
ounces blue cheese;  1 ounce butter;  2 tablespoons port wine;   Freshly
ground pepper to taste;  3 to 4 ounces walnuts, chopped;  3 slices whole wheat
bread;   Thoroughly mix the cheese, butter, wine and pepper. Add the nuts.;   
Toast the bread and cut each slice into quarters. Spread with the mixture.
Makes 12 canapes.;    Variation: Spread cheese mixture on sliced pears or use
to fill celery sticks.;    -- From "American Country; Cheese, Cooking with
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s; Specialty and Farmstead; Cheeses" by <PERSON>Laura Chenel</PERSON> and; <PERSON>Linda
Siegfried</PERSON>; BLUE CHEESE SAUCE FOR LAMB CHOPS;  1/3 cup heavy cream;  6 ounces
blue cheese, crumbled, at room temperature;   Salt and freshly ground black
pepper;   In a small saucepan, bring the heavy cream almost to a boil.;   
Remove from the heat and whisk in the cheese until smooth. Return to low heat
and cook 10 minutes. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Serve over broiled
lamb chops. Also would be excellent with broiled steak.;    -- From "What's
Cooking" by <PERSON>Burt Wolfe</PERSON>; ELEGANT HAM AND CHEESE SANDWICH;  1 firm slice bread; 
1 thin slice baked ham;  1 firm ripe tomato slice, optional;  1 ounces
crumbled Saga or other blue cheese;  1 thin slice Swiss cheese;   Heat
broiler. Lightly toast bread on one side.;    Cover with ham slice and tomato,
if using. Sprinkle with blue cheese; cover with Swiss cheese. Place on a
baking sheet. Broil until cheeses have softened and are beginning to melt.
Makes 1 serving.; BLUE CHEESE SPREAD;  1/4 pound Stilton or other blue cheese
at room temperature;  1/2 cup butter at room temperature;  1 small clove
garlic, minced;  1 tablespoon chopped parsley;  2 tablespoons chopped chives; 
 A few drops of Tabasco;  3 tablespoons Cognac;   Mix all ingredients together
and serve in a crock as a spread with crackers and fruit.;    -- From "<PERSON>James
Beard</PERSON>'s American Cookery"; BLUE CHEESE &amp; BASIL; OMELET;  8 eggs;  3
tablespoons water;  1/2 teaspoon salt;  1/4 teaspoon pepper;  2 tablespoons
butter or margarine;  1 large clove garlic, minced or pressed;  3 ounces
blue-veined cheese, coarsely crumbled;  3 tablespoons chopped fresh basil
leaves or 1 tablespoon dry basil;   In a large bowl, beat eggs, water, salt,
and pepper until blended.;    Heat a 10-inch omelet pan or wide frying pan
with sloping sides over medium-high heat. When pan is hot, add butter and
garlic and stir until butter is melted; tilt pan so butter coats bottom and
sides. Pour in egg mixture and cook just until omelet is almost set, but still
moist and creamy on top; as eggs set, lift cooked portion around edges of pan
with a spatula to allow uncooked portion to flow underneath. Gently shake pan
to keep omelet free.;    Sprinkle omelet with cheese and basil. Continue to
shake pan and lift omelet edges until eggs are set and cheese is melted.;   
Tilt pan over a serving plate and shake pan to slide half the omelet onto
plate. With a flick of the wrist, fold other half of omelet over first half.
Makes 4 servings.;    -- From "Cheese" by Sunset; SPAGHETTI WITH SPICY;
GORGONZOLA SAUCE;  2 fresh jalapeno peppers;  1 ripe plum tomato, peeled,
seeded or 1 canned plum tomato;  1 cup whipping cream;  2 medium garlic
cloves, coarsely chopped;  4 ounces Gorgonzola cheese, cut in a few pieces;  
Salt to taste, if desired;   Cayenne pepper to taste;  8 ounces spaghetti;  2
tablespoons unsalted butter, room temperature;  1 tablespoon minced fresh
parsley leaves;   Wearing gloves, halve jalapeno peppers and discard seeds;
coarsely chop.;    Puree tomato in a food processor and set aside; there is no
need to clean food processor as it will be used in next step.;    Bring cream
to a boil in a small saucepan. Add jalapeno peppers and garlic. Reduce heat to
low and simmer, uncovered, stirring occasionally, 10 minutes. Put Gorgonzola
cheese in food processor. Add 1/2 cup hot cream mixture and process until
blended. Gradually add remaining cream and process mixture until smooth.
Return to saucepan. Add salt and cayenne, if desired.;    Cook pasta. Drain
well. Transfer to a heated serving bowl.;    Meanwhile, reheat sauce to
simmer. Remove from heat; stir in butter and pureed tomato. Add to pasta and
toss. Adjust seasoning. Sprinkle with parsley. Serves 4.;    -- From
"Sensational Pasta" by <PERSON>Faye Levy</PERSON>  </TEXT>
