<HEAD>Tiespeak: The Way To A Man's Psyche</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clothes may make the man, but his tie can reveal
his innermost secrets.
   The color, pattern and style of a man's necktie all provide
clues to his personality and lifestyle, says the Guild of British
Tiemakers, representing 30 manufacturers of ``the British tie,''
that sartorial symbol of the Old Boy Network.
   ``As eyes are reputedly the mirrors of the soul, so ties are the
talisman of the image, a statement by the wearer of their
personality and individuality, an indication of their temperament
and mood, a symbol of the social set in which he does or wants to
belong, a guide to how the wearer sees himself or would like others
to see him,'' according to the guild's survey.
   To help tie wearers and watchers interpret some of the subtle
messages, the guild has issued a guide to ``tiespeak.''
   ``If you want to come across as a strong, confident extrovert
person with strong opinions, choose a brilliantly colored tie or
one with an exaggerated pattern or motif,'' it says.
   ``A man who wears a tie in a plain light color runs the danger
of being a professional <PERSON>Mr. Nice</PERSON>, someone who likes to amuse and
entertain, an arranger of matters rather than a doer.''
   The ``more glowing'' the color of a tie, the more
money-motivated the wearer is likely to be, the guide says. A plain
dark tie, on the other hand, indicates a secretive man who keeps
more than his tie close to his chest.
   The guide says a tie with light and dark stripes of equal width
is the mark of a fence-sitter.
   Wide, light stripes on a dark background suggest the wearer
thinks the best of people and accepts them at face value, while
pessimists generally go for wide, dark stripes on a light
background.
   Multicolored, multiwidth stripes indicate someone who'd love to
do something daring _ if only he dared.
   A striped tie also can blurt out which side of the <LOCATION>Atlantic
Ocean</LOCATION> a man hails from. American tie stripes run from the right
shoulder down toward the left, the opposite of those on a European
tie.
   A tie with dark spots on a light background indicates ``a
wheeler-dealer,'' while light spots on a dark background suggest
``a sheep in wolf's clothing,'' the guide says.
   ``Small, neat geometric patterns are taken to indicate a
planner, a man who likes to create order out of chaos, probably a
good administrator,'' it says.
   A small paisley pattern suggests an upholder of tradition, while
a large paisly print suggests a hedger of bets.
   Ties give away other secrets.
   In <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, a man's personal history can be traced through the
ties in his closet, revealing his school, club and military
background.
   Every British school has its own design, usually striped with
the school colors, which every schoolboy wears as part of his
uniform.
   Upon graduation he moves up to an ``Old School Tie,''
identifying his alma mater. He also may collect a regimental tie,
with symbolic colors and crests.
   The colors of the <ORGANIZATION>Royal Military Academy</ORGANIZATION>'s tie, for example,
represent the ingredients of gunpowder _ yellow for sulphur, blue
for saltpeter and black for carbon. The <ORGANIZATION>Royal Tank Corps</ORGANIZATION> tie
represents the brown mud, red blood and green fields of <LOCATION>Flanders</LOCATION>,
the World War I battlefield.
</TEXT>
