<LEADPARA>  WE ALL customize recipes to suit our own tastes. When readers reply to recipe
requests, the range of ingredients for what is supposedly the same recipe is
often astounding -- and informative.;    Take bread pudding, for instance.
When Lynn Younger of San Jose requested a recipe for a bread pudding that her
family could pick up and eat like cookies, three San Jose readers were quick
to reply. Loretta Del Carlo sent a recipe for old-fashioned bread pudding,
Olga Flores, a Mexican-style version; and Kathy Quesada, a Creole pudding.
Same recipe? Well, not quite. Here's the old-fashioned version followed by
notes on the two variations.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BREAD PUDDING GOES BEYOND BASIC  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Readers' Exchange  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  OLD-FASHIONED BREAD; PUDDING; 3 eggs;  3/4 cups sugar, half white, half brown;
1 teaspoon vanilla; 1 teaspoon cinnamon;  3/4 stick margarine, melted; 5 cups
old bread, cubed;  3/4 cup raisins that have been rinsed in boiling water; 1
quart milk, scalded;   Beat eggs. Add sugar, vanilla, cinnamon and margarine,
mix. Add bread and raisins, mix. Add scaled milk. Mix well and add more milk
if needed. Place in 13-by-9-inch baking dish and bake at 350 degrees for 45
minutes to an 1 hour. Test for doneness with a toothpick.;    VARIATIONS:;   
(box) In the Mexican version, ingredients are: 1 large loaf of stale French
bread torn into pieces, 1 to 1 1/2 quarts milk, 1 cup sugar, 4 eggs, 1/4 stick
margarine, 1 tablespoon cinnamon, 3/4 cup raisins and 1 2-ounce package of
sliced almonds. Soak the bread 1 to 1 1/2 hours in the milk and then drained
before adding the remaining ingredients. Baking dish, oven temperature and
cooking time remain the same.;    (box) The Creole version uses 1 loaf sour
French bread, 1 quart milk, 3 eggs, 1 1/2 cups sugar, 2 teaspoons vanilla, 1
teaspoon grated lemon rind and 1/2 teaspoon ground mace. Soak the bread in
milk and mash until well mixed before adding the remaining ingredients. Baking
dish, oven temperature and cooking time remain the same.; <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> treat; <PERSON>Marty
Eige</PERSON> and <PERSON>Sandy Robnett</PERSON>, both of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, sent this recipe for <PERSON>Mrs. E. W. Wade</PERSON>
of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> who wants to make Key Lime Pie. Eige notes that bottled Key Lime
juice can be purchased in some local stores. A good substitute, she writes, is
the <PERSON>Meyer</PERSON> lemon.;  KEY LIME PIE; 4 eggs, separated; 1 can sweetened condensed
milk;  1/2 cup lime juice; 6 tablespoons sugar;  1/2 teaspoon cream of tartar;
1 baked pie shell;   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Beat egg yolks. Add
condensed milk and lime juice. Beat until thick. Beat 1 egg white until stiff
and fold into mixture. Pour into baked pie shell. For topping, beat 3 egg
whites blending in the sugar and cream of tartar until stiff peaks form.
Spread over top of pie filling. Bake for 20 minutes or until egg whites are
golden brown.; Chewy and sweet; <PERSON>Dolores Corral</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Campbell</ORGANIZATION> requested a recipe
for chewy fruit bar cookies. <PERSON>Christy Baker</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> sends this recipe.;
LEMON BARS; 1 cup margarine;  1/2 cup powdered sugar; 2 cups plus 5
tablespoons flour, divided; 4 eggs; 2 cups granulated sugar; 6 tablespoons
lemon juice; 1 teaspoon baking powder;   Mix margarine, powdered sugar and 2
cups flour until fluffy. Spread in 9-by-13-inch baking pan and pat down. Bake
at 350 degrees for 20 minutes.;    Beat eggs, granulated sugar, lemon juice,
baking powder and 5 tablespoons flour together. Pour over cooled crust. Bake
at 350 degrees for 20 minutes. When cool, sprinkle with additional powdered
sugar, if desired.; Calls for help; <PERSON>Olga Flores</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>  visited <LOCATION>Puerto
Vallarta</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, and tasted tortilla soup. It was great, she wrote, and she
would like a recipe for the soup, which includes beans, sliced tortillas and a
tomato base.;    "We are a soup-and-sandwich family all year round," writes
<PERSON>Priscilla Hosman</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>. She says she has tried many minestrone soup
recipes but none taste as good as that at <LOCATION>Adolph</LOCATION>'s in <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>. Can anyone
supply that recipe?  </TEXT>
