<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Natalie Caudill -- Dallas Morning News; Holiday appetizers:
Cajun shrimp, smoked salmon on toast, potatoes with sour cream and caviar,
stuffed tomatoes and cayenne wafers. (Color)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; ENTERTAINMENT; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  FROM NOW until the New Year, open houses and cocktail parties will fill nearly
as many hours as holiday shopping.;   Hors d'oeuvres are the ideal party food,
whether you're planning a big event or stocking up for when friends drop by.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SHH! DON'T TELL YOUR GUESTS HOW EASY GREAT HORS
D'OEUVRES CAN BE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related article on page 1G of this section.; Camille Kraeplin is a
staff writer of the Dallas Morning News.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Some of the recipes and ideas that follow can be prepared ahead. Others can
be put together in minutes the day of the party. Keep the spread as simple as
you like. The only requirement: Make plenty, especially if you're serving
libations, too.;   It's a good idea to keep some nibbles on hand for
unexpected guests. These snacks can be stored at room temperature in airtight
containers.;   (box) Pita crisps: Split 6 (6-inch-round) pocket breads in half
to make 12 rounds. Brush with 1/4 cup olive oil mixed with 1 clove minced or
pressed garlic and sprinkle with freshly ground black pepper. (You can also
add chopped herbs, if desired.) Cut each round into quarters and arrange in a
single layer on 2 baking sheets. Bake in a 400-degree oven until crisp and
golden, about 5 to 10 minutes. Serve warm or at room temperature.;   (box)
Spiced nuts: Melt 1/4 cup butter. Stir in 1/2 teaspoon Tabasco, 2 teaspoons
Worcestershire sauce and 1 tablespoon garlic salt; coat 2 cups pecan halves
with mixture. Or, stir into butter 1/4 cup prepared chutney and 1 tablespoon
curry powder; coat 2 cups almonds with the mixture. Spread the nuts on a
cookie sheet and bake at 350 degrees for 20 to 25 minutes, until brown,
stirring occasionally. Cool on brown paper.; Quick appetizers;   (check)
Cooked, unpeeled tiny new potatoes, cut in half, chilled and topped with
caviar and sour cream.;   (check) Thin-sliced prosciutto wrapped around wedges
of melon or pieces of peeled pear (dip in lemon juice to prevent discoloring;
pat dry), avocado or banana, fresh figs, cooked asparagus spears or marinated
artichoke hearts.;   (check) Thin rounds of cucumber or carrot topped with
flavored cream cheese and diced tomato or fresh herbs.;   (check) Sandwiches
of cranberry nut bread and cream cheese, cut into small squares or triangles.
Serve on toothpicks.;   (check) Cherry tomatoes, hollowed out and stuffed with
deviled ham, blue cheese, Camembert cheese, a rolled anchovy or smoked
salmon.;   (check) Gorgonzola spread on thin apple or pear slices and
sprinkled with toasted pine nuts.;   (check) Cubes (1-inch) of sharp Cheddar
cheese marinated in brandy for several hours. Serve on toothpicks.;   (check)
Oblong pieces of toast topped with skinless, boneless sardines, tomato puree
and thin slices of mozzarella and broiled until cheese melts.;   (check)
Smoked salmon served with cream cheese on thin-sliced pumpernickel or rye
bread or in Belgian endive leaves. Serve with a lemon wedge, cracked pepper
and a small bowl of creme fraiche.;   (check) Fresh oysters in the shell.
Serve on ice, with lemon wedges and cocktail sauce.;   (check) Buy unusual
olives, such as Grager, Nicoise or Kalamata. Serve in separate bowls.; (hbox);
  The following recipe is from "Season of Wonder: Christmas <DATE>1990</DATE>" (<ORGANIZATION>Heritage
House</ORGANIZATION>).; CAJUN SHRIMP; 1 pound extra-large shrimp, peeled; 1 tablespoon lime
juice; 1/2 teaspoon garlic powder; 1/2 teaspoon onion powder; 1/4 teaspoon
thyme; 1/4 teaspoon salt; 1/8 to 1/4 teaspoon red pepper; 1/8 teaspoon black
pepper; Lime wedges;  Toss shrimp with lime juice in bowl. Mix garlic powder,
onion powder, thyme, salt, red pepper and black pepper in small bowl. Sprinkle
over shrimp; toss to coat well.;   Spray large skillet with non-stick cooking
spray. Heat until hot. Add shrimp. Cook for 3 minutes, or until shrimp are
pink, stirring constantly. Spoon into serving dish. Chill, covered, for 1 hour
or longer. Garnish with lime wedges. Makes 15 servings.; (hbox);   This recipe
appears in "<PERSON>Martha Stewart</PERSON>'s Christmas" (<PERSON>Clarkson N. Potter</PERSON>, <MONEY>$18.95</MONEY>).; CAYENNE
PEPPER WAFERS; 1/2 pound Gruyere cheese, grated; 1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted
butter, at room temperature; 1 teaspoon cayenne pepper; 1 teaspoon salt; 2 1/2
cups sifted all-purpose flour; 1 cup chopped walnuts or pecans;  Preheat oven
to 350 degrees. Cream cheese and butter. Sift together cayenne pepper, salt
and flour and add gradually to butter mixture. Add nuts; mix well. Divide
dough in half and shape into logs 1 1/2 inches in diameter. Wrap well and
refrigerate for at least 1 hour.;   Line baking sheets with parchment paper.
With a sharp knife, cut logs into 1/4-inch slices; place wafers 1 to 2 inches
apart on baking sheets.;   Bake for 15 to 20 minutes, until lightly colored.
Cool and store in an airtight container. Makes 6 dozen.; (hbox);   The
following recipe is from cookbook author <PERSON>Abby Mandel.</PERSON>; BROILED CHEESE CAPS; 1
cup shredded Swiss cheese; 1/2 cup light mayonnaise; 2 large garlic cloves,
pureed in garlic press; 2 teaspoons fresh lemon juice; Salt and freshly ground
pepper to taste; 32 large (about 1 3/4 inches in diameter) firm white
mushrooms; Hungarian paprika;  Combine cheese, mayonnaise, garlic and lemon
juice in small bowl. Season to taste. Refrigerate in a covered, airtight
container for as long as 3 days.;   Remove mushroom stems and reserve for
another use. Gently brush mushroom caps to clean them. Do not wash them. Fill
mushroom caps with 1/2 teaspoon cheese mixture. Sprinkle with paprika. Place
single layer on baking sheet. (Filled mushrooms can be refrigerated overnight;
let come to room temperature before broiling.);   Broil about 6 inches from
heat until bubbly and golden, about 2 minutes. Serve warm. Makes 32 servings.  </TEXT>
