<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN "visions of sugarplums dance in your head" this holiday season, you might
want to make them dance on your table with one of the winning recipes from the
annual Mission Peak Heritage Foundation's Victorian Dessert Faire Contest.
Held at Fremont's historic Shinn House on Sept. 15, the Dessert Faire
attracted more than 25 entrants. Vying for the honor of winning
Victorian-style prize ribbons, participants baked up desserts that were judged
in four categories: pies, cakes, cookies and pastries.;   It takes a
discerning palate to withstand tasting so many sweets in one session. If you
are not careful, everything begins to taste the same. Dessert Faire organizer,
Sherry Niswonger, put together a team of judges with taste buds potent enough
to weather the sugary onslaught. Tom Blalock, head of Fremont Public Works,
Paula Artak, local artist and Rose Thatcher, a founding member of Mission Peak
Historical Society helped in making the award decisions.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  The Weekly, Part 2  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VICTORIAN DESSERTS A SWEET DELIGHT
RECIPES FOR PIES, CAKES, COOKIES AND PASTRIES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Weekly Cook  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "Entries were judged on taste, texture and overall appearance," <PERSON>Niswonger</PERSON>
said. "Appearance is really a winning factor. Cookies displayed beautifully on
a doily-covered platter are much more inviting than cookies submitted on a
flimsy white paper plate.";   Give this year's winning recipes a try and see
if you agree with the judges.;  FIRST PLACE COOKIE RECIPE; HERSHEY'S DOUBLE;
CHOCOLATE MINT DESSERT;  <PERSON>Stephanie Telles</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Fremont</LOCATION>;  Your favorite brownies
recipe for 13x9x2-inch baking pan;  Mint cream layer:; 2 cups confectioners
sugar; 1/2 cup softened butter; 1/2 tsp. mint extract; 3 drops green food
coloring;  Chocolate topping layer:; 6 tablespoons butter; 1 cup <ORGANIZATION>Hershey</ORGANIZATION>'s
mint chocolate chips; Make brownies according to your recipe. Cool completely
in pan. In the meantime, in a small mixing bowl, beat all of the mint cream
layer ingredients until well-blended. Spread evenly over cooled brownies and
refrigerate until well-chilled.;   In a small microwave-proof bowl, melt the
butter and the mint chips uncovered on high for 1 to 1 1/2 minutes, or until
just melted. Stir the mixture to combine. Pour chocolate topping over mint
cream layer and chill in the refrigerator until set.;  FIRST PLACE CAKE
RECIPE; CHOCOLATE APRICOT PECAN TORTE;  Decorated with apricot roses and
chocolate leaves;  <PERSON>Marty Jones</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Fremont</LOCATION>;  (Note: A great do-ahead dessert); 
14-16 servings; 1/3 cup cognac; 1 1/4 cups dried apricots (about 6 ounces),
cut into 1/4-inch pieces; 1 tablespoon butter, room temperature; 3 tablespoons
dry bread crumbs; 3/4 cup (1 1/2 sticks) unsalted butter, room temperature; 1
cup sugar; 5 eggs, room temperature; 6 ounces semisweet chocolate, melted and
cooled; 1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla; 2/3 cups dry bread crumbs; 1 1/2 cups
coarsely chopped pecans; 1 tablespoon all purpose flour;  Chocolate Icing:;
1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa powder; 1/2 cup sugar; 1/2 cup whipping cream; 1/4
cup ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter, cut into small pieces;  Apricot glaze:; 2
tablespoons cognac; 1/2 cup apricot jam; 1/2 cup pecan halves optional; For
cake: Heat cognac in a medium saucepan until just hot. Remove from heat and
mix in apricots. Soak 15 minutes. Strain apricots, reserving any soaking
liquid for glaze. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Butter 8 1/2-inch springform
pan with 1 tablespoon butter. Dust with the 3 tablespoons of bread crumbs.
Using electric mixer, cream butter until light and fluffy. Gradually beat in
sugar. Beat in eggs one at a time -- the mixture may look curdled. Add
chocolate and vanilla. Mix in 2/3 cup of bread crumbs. Combine pecans and
flour and blend into batter. Fold in apricots. Spoon batter into prepared pan.
Bake until tester inserted in center comes out clean, about 50 minutes. Run
knife around edge of cake. Invert onto platter. Slide sheets of waxed paper
under edges of cake.;   For Icing: Stir all ingredients in top of double
boiler over simmering water until mixture is shiny and smooth -- about 5
minutes. Cool icing for 5 minutes, stirring occasionally. Pour icing over
cake, tilting cake to cover evenly. Using thin flat spatula, spread icing over
top and sides of cake. Refrigerate until icing is firm.;   For glaze: Add
enough cognac to soaking liquid reserved from apricots to measure 2
tablespoons. Combine with jam in heavy small saucepan. Stir over medium low
heat until melted. Strain through fine sieve into small bowl. Cool until
tepid, about 5 minutes. Pour glaze over top of cake. Using thin metal spatula,
spread evenly. Do not let glaze drip down sides of cake. Arrange pecans around
upper edge of cake, ends touching. Discard paper. Refrigerate cake until glaze
is set. (Cake can be prepared up to one day ahead.);   Arrange apricot roses
in center of torte. Place large chocolate leaf between each flower. Place
smaller leaf between each large leaf. Let stand at room temperature 1 hour
before serving.; 3 Apricot Roses; 12 moist dried apricots;  Roll each apricot
out, sticky side down between 2 sheets of waxed paper to thickness of
one-sixteenth inch. Roll one up tightly, sticky side in, to form the center of
the bud. Wrap another apricot around bud, sticky side in, pressing gently to
adhere. Repeat with 2 more apricots, overlapping half of each previous one.
Gently bend top of outer 3 apricots outward to form petals. Place toothpick
horizontally through base of rose. Cut off apricot below toothpick to form
flat base. Repeat with remaining apricots. Place roses on plate and freeze 30
minute. (Can be prepared three days ahead. Cover tightly and refrigerate.)
Discard toothpicks before arranging roses on cake.; 6 Chocolate Leaves;  3
ounces semisweet chocolate, melted;  3 large rose leaves with stems;  3 medium
rose leaves with stems; Spread chocolate over veined side of each leaf with a
small metal spatula, being careful not to drip on edges. Place on plate
chocolate side up. Freeze until just firm, about 10 minutes. Starting at the
stem end, gently peel leaf away from chocolate, freezing briefly if too soft
to work. (The chocolate leaves can be prepared 1 week ahead and refrigerated.
Wrap tightly.);  FIRST PLACE PIE; PECAN PIE;  <PERSON>Stephanie Telles</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Fremont</LOCATION>;  3
egg whites;  1 cup sugar; 1/4 tsp. salt; 1/2 cup chopped pecans;  20 Ritz
crackers, finely crushed; Beat egg whites until stiff. Add sugar and salt
beating briefly to distribute evenly. Fold in pecans and crackers. Place in
greased pie pan and bake in preheated 350-degree oven for 25 minutes. Cool
completely. Spread Cool Whip on the top and chill at least 3 hours.;  FIRST
PLACE PASTRY; <LOCATION>BAKLAVA</LOCATION>;  <PERSON>Mary Niblack</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Fremont</LOCATION>; 1 lb. filo dough, (found in
freezer section of grocery store); 1 cup melted butter; 2 cups walnuts, finely
chopped; 2 tablespoons sugar; 1 teaspoon vanilla;  Baklava Syrup:; 1 cup
water; 2 cups sugar; 1 cup honey; 1 teaspoon lemon juice; 1 teaspoon vanilla;
1 cinnamon stick; 2-3 cloves; 1 orange slice; 1 lemon slice; Prepare syrup
ahead (may be stored in refrigerator up to 2 weeks). Place all syrup
ingredients in heavy saucepan and boil 2 minutes. Cool until ready for use,
then remove cinnamon stick cloves and fruit slices. In a small bowl, mix
walnuts, sugar and vanilla. Butter a 9x13-inch pan. Place one-third of filo
sheets in pan, one at a time, brushing each with melted butter. Sprinkle
one-half of the walnuts, sugar and vanilla mixture evenly over buttered filo.
Add another one-third of the filo, melted butter, followed by another layer of
the remaining nut mixture. Top with another buttered layer of filo. With a
very sharp knife, cut through all the layers, making 2-inch diamond shapes.
Bake in a preheated 300-degree oven until golden brown. Pour syrup over the
hot pastry and allow to stand for at least one hour to soak up the syrup.
Serves 16 to 20.;   IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; For more information about becoming
involved in the <ORGANIZATION>Mission Peak Heritage Foundation</ORGANIZATION>, and next year's Victorian
Dessert Faire, call <PERSON>Sherry Nighswonger</PERSON> at (510) 656-9076.  </TEXT>
