<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Succulent Bartlett pears, available now to November, offer a fresh taste for
pies, salads, breads and spreads; BARTLETT BISTRO SALAD  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JUICY FRUIT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  2 fresh <PERSON>Bartlett</PERSON> pears, cored, sliced; 4 cups each spinach leaves and red leaf
lettuce torn, loosely packed; 2 cups romaine lettuce or other greens torn,
loosely packed; 6 tablespoons olive oil; 2 chicken breast halves, skinned,
deboned, cut into 1- to 1 1/2-inch strips; 1/2 cup walnut halves; 2
tablespoons minced green onions; 2 tablespoons cider vinegar; Salt and pepper;
2 ounces Roquefort cheese or blue cheese, crumbled ( 1/4 cup);  Place pears in
a medium bowl; set aside. Combine spinach and lettuces in a large salad bowl;
set aside. Heat 2 tablespoons olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high
heat, add chicken and walnuts; saute until chicken is cooked through, about 4
to 5 minutes. Remove from skillet and combine with pears. Reduce heat to
medium, add onions and cook, stirring frequently, until translucent, about 2
minutes. Pour in vinegar and bring to a boil, scraping brown bits from bottom
of skillet. Remove from heat; whisk in remaining 4 tablespoons olive oil, add
salt and pepper to taste. Pour over pear and chicken mixture and thoroughly
mix. Add to greens and gently toss to coat. Sprinkle with cheese. Serve with
French baguette bread. Makes 4 servings.; One serving: 482 calories, 20 gm.
carbohydrate, 25 gm. protein, 36 gm. fat, 355 mg. sodium and 54 mg.
cholesterol.; FRESH SPICED PEAR BREAD; 1/2 cup butter, softened; 1 cup
granulated sugar; 2 eggs; 3 fresh <PERSON>Bartlett</PERSON> pears, chopped (about 2 1/3 cups);
2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour; 2 teaspoons baking soda; 1 teaspoon salt; 2
teaspoons ground cinnamon; 1/2 teaspoon ground cloves; 1/2 teaspoon ground
nutmeg;  Grease and flour a 8 1/2-inch loaf pan. In large bowl, beat butter
and sugar. Beat in eggs and pears. In separate bowl, sift together remaining
ingredients; blend into pear mixture. Spoon batter into pan. Bake in
350-degree oven for 60 to 75 minutes or until wooden pick inserted in center
comes out clean. Cool in pan 5 minutes. Turn out onto wire rack to cool
completely. Makes 16 servings.; HONEYED PEAR BUTTER; 3 fresh <PERSON>Bartlett</PERSON> pears,
cored, chopped; 1/2 cup water; 1 tablespoon honey; 1 teaspoon unsalted butter;
1/8 teaspoon. ground cinnamon;  Place pears in saucepan with remaining
ingredients. Cook over medium heat, stirring frequently, 15 to 20 minutes or
microwave, covered, in microwave-safe dish on high 3 minutes or until pears
are tender. Cool to room temperature. Puree drained pears. May be stored in
refrigerator, covered, up to 2 weeks. Serve as spread on bread or as an
accompaniment with grilled or roast poultry. Makes about 1 pint.; GINGER
WAFFLES WITH SHERRIED PEAR SAUCE; Waffles:; 2 cups buttermilk pancake mix
(check package directions for list of required ingredients.); 2 teaspoons
ground ginger; Sherried pear sauce:; 2 1/2 tablespoons cornstarch; 1
tablespoon packed brown sugar; 1 cup apple juice; 1/4 cup cream sherry; 1
tablespoon margarine or butter; 2 fresh <PERSON>Bartlett</PERSON> pears, cored and sliced; 
Preheat waffle iron. In medium bowl, combine all ingredients, except sauce,
and make waffles according to package directions. In medium saucepan, combine
cornstarch and sugar; stir in juice and sherry. Bring to a boil, stirring
constantly until thickened. Add margarine and pears and simmer 5 minutes
longer or until pears are tender. Serve waffles on warmed plates; pass sauce.
Makes 3 to 4 large waffles or 6 to 7 Belgian waffles.; Tips: Double or triple
the recipe and make your own toaster waffles. Stack cooled waffles between
waxed paper. Wrap in foil and freeze.; One serving: 396 calories, 66 gm.
carbohydrate, 4 gm. protein, 11 gm. fat, 743 mg. sodium and 0 mg.
cholesterol.; PEAR MELBA PIE; Raspberry Filling:; 1 10-ounce package frozen
red raspberries, thawed; 1 envelope plain gelatin; 3/4 cup boiling water; 1
teaspoon lemon juice; 1/2 cup sugar; 1/8 teaspoon salt; 1 cup fresh
raspberries (optional); Cheese Filling:; 1 8-ounce package cream cheese,
softened; 1/4 teaspoon grated lemon peel; 2 tablespoons half-and-half; 1
9-inch pie or tart shell, baked; 3 fresh <PERSON>Bartlett</PERSON> pears, peeled, cored,
sliced;  To prepare raspberry filling, drain frozen raspberries, reserving
liquid. Sprinkle gelatin over 1/4 cup reserved juice. Stir boiling water into
gelatin and add lemon juice, sugar and salt; stir until dissolved. Add
remaining raspberry liquid, frozen and fresh raspberries. Chill until mixture
will mound on spoon.;   To prepare cheese filling, combine cheese, lemon peel
and half-and-half. Spread cheese filling on baked pastry shell. Arrange pear
slices decoratively over filling. Cover with gelatin mixture, mounding
raspberries in middle. Chill until set. Makes 8 servings.; One serving: 331
calories, 41 gm. carbohydrate, 5 gm. protein, 17 gm. fat, 303 mg. sodium and
32 mg. cholesterol.; PEAR GRAPEFRUIT SLUSH; 2 fresh <PERSON>Bartlett</PERSON> pears, pared,
cored, diced (1 1/2 cups); 1 12-ounce can unsweetened grapefruit juice; 2 cups
ice cubes, cracked;  Turn pears into blender with grapefruit juice and ice.
Whirl until smooth. Makes 4 servings.; One serving: 80 calories, 19 gm.
carbohydrate, 1 gm. protein, trace fat, 1 mg. sodium and 0 mg. cholesterol.;
PEAR MUSTARD; 1 fresh <PERSON>Bartlett</PERSON> pear, cored, quartered; 3 tablespoons
Dijon-style mustard; 2 tablespoons sour cream;  Combine ingredients in
blender; whirl until smooth. Use as a spread with your favorite sandwich
ingredients. Makes 1 cup.; One serving: 12 calories, 2 gm. carbohydrate, trace
protein, 1 gm. fat, 38 mg. sodium and 1 mg. cholesterol.; <ORGANIZATION>CABERNET PEAR</ORGANIZATION> TART;
1 bottle (750 ml.) cabernet sauvignon wine; 1 lemon, sliced; 1 cinnamon stick;
2 whole cloves; 1/2 cup sugar; 4 fresh <PERSON>Bartlett</PERSON> pears, pared, cores removed
from bottom; 1 12-inch-square sheet frozen puff pastry, thawed; 4 teaspoons
sugar; 1 egg, beaten with 1 tablespoon water; Peach or apricot jam thinned
with orange juice;  Place wine, lemon, cinnamon stick, cloves and sugar in a
2-quart microwave-safe deep casserole dish. Cook on high 10 minutes. Add pears
and cook on high 8 minutes or until tender when pierced on bottom with a sharp
knife. Let stand in poaching liquid until cool enough to handle. (Pears may be
poached the night before and refrigerated.) Cut four 5-inch rounds from puff
pastry sheet. Place on baking sheet; slice each pear lengthwise into 1/4-inch
slices, keeping pear intact at top. Gently fan out the slices. Place one pear
on each pastry round. Sprinkle each with 1 teaspoon sugar. Brush edges of
pastry with beaten egg mixture. Bake in 400-degree oven about 15 to 20 minutes
or until pastry is puffed and brown. Brush each tart with warmed apricot or
peach jam thinned with a little orange juice. Serve warm with creme fraiche or
whipped cream. Makes 4 tarts.; One serving: 557 calories, 76 gm. carbohydrate,
5 gm. protein, 15 gm. fat, 393 mg. sodium and 69 mg. cholesterol.  </TEXT>
