<LEADPARA>  FOR SALMON lovers, there's nothing quite like this finny fare with a smoky
taste. Cooks, however, are often stymied by complex recipes for smoked
salmon.;   When Amelia Yee of San Jose requested a recipe for simple smoked
salmon, Dolly Greenfield of Portola Valley responded. "This recipe has been
handed down to me and is therefore tried and true," Greenfield writes. "It
freezes fantastically, too."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  READER OFFERS EASY STEPS TO SMOKE-FLAVORED SALMON  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Readers' Exchange  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  "SMOKED" SALMON; 8 teaspoons pickling salt; 2 tablespoons brown sugar; 1 1/2 
teaspoons liquid smoke; 1 tablespoon oil; <MONEY>2 pounds</MONEY> of 2-ounce fresh salmon
fillets; Heavy-duty aluminum foil; Plastic freezer bags;  Make a paste of the
salt, brown sugar, liquid smoke and oil. Place a large piece of foil on table
and lay fish on it, skin side down. On flesh part, rub in paste mixture. Do
not rub on skin side. Wrap tightly in the foil. Place in plastic freezer bag
because it will leak out of foil during process. . It's very important to
place plastic bag in an enamel pan or another freezer bag. Leave in
refrigerator for two weeks. Then unwrap fish. Wash off paste, rewrap in foil
and leave in freezer for at least two days. It is then ready to serve. To cut,
partially defrost because if fish is too soft, it will not slice evenly.;  
Thanks also to <PERSON>Herman Stern</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Los Gatos</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Gail Shirley</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> for
their recipe contributions.; Sassy sauce; <PERSON>Sharon Runninghawk</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION>
wanted to know how to make enchilada sauce from scratch, and readers <PERSON>Lynne
Duell</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Lorraine Mavraedis</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Fremont</LOCATION> responded with their
favorite recipes. The first is from <ORGANIZATION>HP</ORGANIZATION> Books' "Mexican Cookery" by <PERSON>Barbara
Hansen.</PERSON>; SALSA PARA ENCHILADAS; 8 dried <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> chilies; 1 1/2 tablespoons
vegetable oil; 1 garlic clove; 1 tablespoon all-purpose flour; 1 teaspoon
vinegar; 3/4 teaspoon salt; 1/4 teaspoon dried leaf oregano, crushed; 1/4
teaspoon ground cumin; 1/8 teaspoon garlic powder;  Wash chilies thoroughly.
Place in large saucepan and cover generously with water. Cover and bring to
boil. Remove from heat and let stand 45 minutes, or until softened. Drain
chilies, reserving liquid for soaking. Pull off stems. Slit chilies open and
rinse off seeds. Place chilies plus 1 cup soaking liquid in blender or food
processor and puree. Pour into a sieve and rub through sieve into bowl to
eliminate small bits of peel. Rinse blender with another 1 cup soaking liquid
and pour over remaining pulp in sieve.;   Heat oil and garlic in a medium
saucepan. When oil is fragrant with garlic, discard garlic clove. Stir in
flour until mixture is smooth. Cook about 1 minute. Add pureed chili mixture
and remaining ingredients. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat. Cook and stir until
slightly thickened. Taste and add more salt, if needed. Makes about 2 1/3
cups. For a hotter sauce, substitute 2 or 3 dried <LOCATION>New Mexico</LOCATION> chilies for 2 or
3 <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> chilies.; (hbox); SALSA DE CHILI EN <LOCATION>POLVO</LOCATION>; 3 tablespoons oil; 2
tablespoons all-purpose flour; 1/4 cup mild red chili powder; 2 cups beef
broth; 2 10 1/2-ounce cans tomato puree; 1/2 teaspoon dried leaf oregano,
crushed; 1/4 teaspoon ground cumin; 1/4 teaspoon garlic powder; Salt;  Heat
oil in large saucepan. Stir in flour and cook 1 minute. Stir in chili powder.
Add beef broth, tomato puree, oregano, cumin and garlic powder. Taste and add
salt if needed. Simmer 15 minutes. Makes about 4 2/3 cups, enough for 12
enchiladas.; Key lime sources; <PERSON>Carolyn Schreck</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> writes that
<PERSON>Lorraine Ghoster</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> can find Key Lime juice at Cosentinos' on <LOCATION>Bascom
Avenue</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>San Jose.</LOCATION>; Calls for help; <PERSON>Lori Mascar</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> is looking for a
lemon bar recipe made with cake mix and topped with cream cheese, and a recipe
for a thick teriyaki sauce.;   <PERSON>Linda Stuckey</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Saratoga</LOCATION> has long searched for
a recipe for chocolate mousse torte. She has ruled out Sweet Things in <LOCATION>Tiburon</LOCATION>
and the <LOCATION>Hyatt House Mediterranean</LOCATION>, who would not share their recipes for a
similar torte. She does know that the recipe contains two kinds of chocolate
and chocolate wafer crumbs. She thinks the filling is not baked.;   <PERSON>Chris
Aycock</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION> is looking for a recipe for garlic jelly.  </TEXT>
