<LEADPARA>  IT IS possible to cater a wedding reception at home and live to tell about it.
I've done it, and so can you.;    My son married in a late-afternoon ceremony
in our home, with almost 50 guests in attendance. We have a family tradition
of celebrating everything -- including weddings -- at home, because we like
the warmth and friendliness of a familiar setting.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOW TO CATER A WEDDING IN YOUR HOME  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related article this page
Bubbly for toasting, Page 7D
Kyra Effren is a Dallas food stylist and free-lance writer.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     There's an added bonus: A home wedding costs a fraction of what a more
formal affair would cost, especially if you prepare the food yourself (except
for the cake), as I did. This is no small consideration. And if the wedding is
in your house, you have those leftovers to enjoy.;    The key to surviving and
even enjoying the event is hiring kitchen help for the day of the ceremony.
This leaves the worrying to them. Here's how to pull it off.;    (check)
First, make a list. You'll need all the things for a home wedding that you
would for any other wedding: flowers, food, cakes, drinks, photographer, the
guest book, music and help with serving the food. Interview and hire the
people you need.;    If you are fixing the food yourself, leave all but that
to friends and professionals.;    (check) Plan what you will drape the serving
tables with. Then buy wedding napkins and coordinating disposable plates,
utensils, cups and glasses for a minimum of clean-up.;    (check) Arrange for
flowers and the wedding cakes to be delivered the morning of the wedding.;   
(check) Include about six hors d'oeuvres and two types of cookies on the menu.
In choosing recipes, look for dishes that can be prepared ahead of time, even
frozen. Choose bite-size, easy-to-handle foods to reduce the possibility of
spills and stains. The food should be able to hold up for a few hours.;   
(check) Set up a timetable of when each recipe will be prepared and how it
will be stored. I started cooking a month in advance. Package each item with
instructions on thawing and final preparation. As you cook, assign serving
platters and containers (sticking a small label on the underside is a fine
idea) for each dish. Borrow extras if needed.;    The day before;  (check)
Position plates, utensils and serving pieces -- everything except the food and
flowers -- on the draped tables.;    (check)  Chill the champagne and start
defrosting the frozen dishes.;    (check) Reconfirm that flowers and cake will
be delivered the next day. You may want to reconfirm with your kitchen help,
photographer and other professionals too.;    (check) Double-check all written
instructions (assemblage of your previously prepared foods, etc.) for whoever
will be in charge of the kitchen. Leave separate lists for the kitchen help
and for the server.;    That morning;  (check) Set out platters and bowls for
the caterer, and arrange any food that can be prepared in advance.;    This is
where it ended for me. Three hours before the wedding, the kitchen staff took
over. I walked out of the kitchen, went to have my hair done, and returned as
a guest at my son's wedding. I had wonderful time.;    The following recipes
would be equally at home at any festive occasion.;      SMOKED SALMON ON <PERSON>BROWN</PERSON>
BREAD;  2 sides smoked salmon, pre-sliced;   <ORGANIZATION>Capers</ORGANIZATION>, drained;  2 lemons,
sliced;  2 loaves cocktail brown bread;  1/2 to 1 pound butter;   Set salmon
on serving platters; decorate with drained capers and thin lemon slices.
Surround salmon with thinly sliced buttered brown bread. (Recipe may be
assembled one day ahead. Arrange salmon slices on platter. Cut and butter
bread; cover with damp cloth, then cover tightly with foil; refrigerate.) Two
sides serve 50 people.;    (hbox);    TOAST CUPS WITH CURRIED ONION-CELERY
FILLING;  1 loaf white bread;  4 to 6 ounces melted butter;  1/2 cup sliced
almonds;  1/2 cup mayonnaise;  2 tablespoons ketchup;  1 cup finely chopped
celery;  1/2 cup finely chopped onion;  1/2 teaspoon curry powder;   Pinch
salt;  1/2 cup chopped dates;   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Cut crusts from
bread slices; cut 4-inch rounds from each slice. Roll thin with rolling pin.
Brush with melted butter and press into bite-size muffin pans to form cases.; 
  Bake until lightly browned and crisp, 5 to 8 minutes. Remove from oven and
allow to cool. Pack into freezer bags and freeze.;    Combine remaining
ingredients for filling. Refrigerate until ready to use, up to 2 days.;    To
serve: Defrost toast cups. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Spoon the filling into
the cups. Heat for 3 to 5 minutes. Makes about 24 servings. Recipe can be
doubled.;    (hbox);    MINI CHICKEN; HERB BISCUITS;  2 cups flour;  1
teaspoon sugar;  1 tablespoon baking powder;  1/2 teaspoon salt;  1/4 cup
chopped fresh herbs, (parsley, chives, basil);  6 tablespoons shortening;  2/3
cup milk;  1 1/2 pounds thinly sliced deli chicken;   Honey mustard;   Chutney
mayonnaise (recipe follows);   Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Stir together the
dry ingredients and herbs. Cut in the shortening, then stir in the milk to
make a soft dough. Knead lightly on a floured board and roll out to about 1/3
inch thick. Cut into 1 1/2-inch rounds.;    Set on ungreased cookie sheet and
bake for 7 to 10 minutes or until puffed and light brown. Remove from oven and
allow to cool, then wrap immediately and freeze.;    To serve: Defrost the
biscuits. Cut rounds of chicken the same diameter as the biscuits. Split the
biscuits and fill with the rounds of chicken. Garnish with the mustard or
mayonnaise or allow the guests to choose their own. Makes 25 servings.;   
<ORGANIZATION>Chutney Mayonnaise</ORGANIZATION>: Stir together equal parts of chutney and mayonnaise.;   
(hbox);     BRIE CHEESE "CAKE" WITH GRAPE-WALNUT GARNISH;  1  12-inch brie
round (about 4 pounds);  1 1/2 cups cream, whipped;  1 pound green grapes;  1
pound red grapes;  1 cup whole walnuts;   Crackers;   Bring the cheese to room
temperature. Cut around the inside wall of the crust and carefully remove the
cheese, leaving the crust to form a case. (If you prefer not to eat the rind,
trim the top of the cheese off before cutting.);    Beat the cheese with the
cream until light. Spoon or pipe the creamed cheese back into the shell.
Decorate with the grapes and the nuts in a pattern of your choice.
Refrigerate.;    To serve: Bring to room temperature. Serve with crackers.
Makes 50 servings.;    (hbox);    MINI PUFF PASTRY SHELLS WITH TOMATO SHRIMP
SAUCE;  48 mini puff pastry shells (2 boxes, store-bought);  1 small onion,
chopped;  1 small green pepper, chopped;  1 clove garlic, crushed;  2
tablespoons oil;  1 16-ounce can crushed tomatoes;  1 tablespoon minced fresh
cilantro;  1 jalapeno, seeded and chopped;  1 tablespoon vinegar;  1 1/2
pounds salad shrimp;   Bake pastry shells according to package instructions.
(Shells can be baked up to 2 days in advance; store in an airtight
container.);    Saute the onion, green pepper and garlic in the oil until
soft. Remove from heat and cool. Mix with remaining ingredients except shrimp;
refrigerate until ready to serve.;    To serve: Heat the cooked pastry shells
for 10 minutes at 300 degrees. Heat the sauce over medium heat until just
bubbling; add shrimp. Spoon the sauce into shells. Makes 48 servings.;   
(hbox);    RED AND GREEN TORTA;  8 ounces cream cheese, softened;  8 ounces
butter, softened;  1/4 cup sun-dried tomato paste;  1/4 cup pesto sauce
(store-bought);   Fresh basil leaves;   Combine the cream cheese and butter.
Mix until smooth. Line a 2- or 3-cup bowl or mold with damp cheesecloth,
leaving enough cloth to hang over the edge of the container.;    Spoon 1/3 of
the butter mixture into the bowl. Smooth. Spread the tomato paste over the
mixture. Spread on another 1/3 of the butter mixture, then top with the pesto.
Spread on the remaining butter mixture.;    Press the mixture down to remove
air pockets. Fold the excess cheesecloth over the top. Cover with foil and
refrigerate 12 hours or more.;    To unmold: Open the foil and the cheesecloth
on the top of the torta. Place the serving plate upside down on top and invert
the torta. Remove the bowl and peel off the cheesecloth. Cover with plastic
wrap and refrigerate.;    To serve: Bring to room temperature; decorate with
fresh basil leaves. Serve with crackers. Makes 50 servings.;    (hbox);    
PECAN LIME BARS;  2/3 cup confectioners' sugar, plus extra for garnish;  2/3
cup chopped pecans;  1 cup melted butter;  2 cups flour;  4 eggs;  2 cups
sugar;  2 tablespoons grated lime rind, plus extra for garnish;  1/2 cup fresh
lime juice;  1 teaspoon baking powder;  3 tablespoons flour;   Preheat oven to
350 degrees. Stir the confectioners' sugar and pecans into the melted butter
until smooth, then stir in the flour. Press dough into a 10-by-15-inch
jellyroll pan. Bake for about 25 minutes or until very light brown. Remove
from oven.;    Stir together the remaining ingredients and pour over the base.
Return to oven and bake another 25 to 30 minutes or until the filling is set.
Remove from oven, cool and cut into small squares. Freeze (in baking container
if possible).;    To serve: Thaw, separate into squares and sprinkle with
confectioners' sugar. Garnish with threads of lime zest. Makes 96 small
squares.;    (hbox);    CUSTARD SPRITZ COOKIES;  1 1/2 cups flour;  5
envelopes Bird's Dessert Mix (1 cup);  1 teaspoon baking powder;  4 ounces
butter;  3/4 cup sugar;  2 eggs;  1 teaspoon vanilla extract;   Decorations:
chopped nuts, colored sugar or sprinkles (optional);   Stir dry ingredients
together. Cream the butter and sugar together until light. Beat eggs 1 at a
time into butter-sugar mixture, then stir in vanilla. Stir in the dry
ingredients. Refrigerate 20 minutes.;    Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Pipe or
spoon batter onto greased cookie sheet (this batter does very well with a
cookie press). Sprinkle with nuts, sugar or sprinkles and bake for about 10
minutes or until the cookies are light brown. Cool, then freeze in bags. Makes
6 dozen.;  MENU;  Smoked salmon on; brown bread;  Toast cups with curried;
onion-celery filling; Brie cheese "cake" with; grape-walnut garnish; Mini
chicken herb biscuits; Mini puff pastry shells; with tomato shrimp sauce; Red
and green torta; with crackers; Pecan Lime Bars; Custard Spritz Cookies;
Wedding cake, <ORGANIZATION>Groom</ORGANIZATION>'s cake  </TEXT>
