<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Avoid the annual last-minute scramble for holiday presents; with these recipes
for gifts sure to be one-of-a-kind  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EARLY ELF  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   CUSTOM FRUIT CAKE; 1 cup butter; 1 cup dark brown sugar; 1/4 cup molasses; 6
eggs; 2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour; 1/2 teaspoon salt; 1 teaspoon baking
powder; <ORGANIZATION>Juice</ORGANIZATION> and rind of 1 orange; <ORGANIZATION>Juice</ORGANIZATION> and rind of 1 lemon; 1 cup pitted
dates, cut into large pieces (see note); 2 cups golden raisins; 2 cups dark
raisins; 2 cups currants; 1 cup dried cherries; 3 cups pecans, walnuts or
almonds or combination; 1 cup sweetened dried pineapple, cut up; 1/2 cup apple
juice, sherry, brandy or orange juice; 1/2 cup brandy or rum to brush on cake
as it matures;  Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Grease 8 1/2-by-3-inch round
English cake pan or pan of similar size, two 9-by-3-inch loaf pans or multiple
smaller pans; cut baking paper to fit bottom of each pan.;   Beat the butter,
brown sugar and molasses until light. Beat in eggs, one at a time. Stir
together flour, salt and baking powder. Set aside 1/2 cup of this mixture to
dust fruit.;   Beat the orange and lemon juice and rinds into the batter, then
stir in the flour mixture by hand.;   Combine fruits and nuts and toss with
the reserved flour mixture. Stir into the batter, together with the apple
juice or other liquid. Pile into prepared pan, filling three-fourths full.
Bake 1 1/2 hours for large round cake, 1 hour for loaf pans or about 50
minutes for mini pans. Reduce oven heat to 275 degrees, cover top of cake with
foil and cook for the same amount of time again.;   Allow cake to cool in pan,
then invert onto cooling rack. Brush cake generously with brandy or rum. Wrap
in foil and store in airtight tin. Brush cake every few days with more brandy
or rum. Cake will be ready to eat in 1 month, or store up to 3 months, tightly
wrapped.;   Note: If you use your own mix of fruit, use 9 cups of whole or
cut-up fruit. Choose from candied or dried cherries, dried apricots, any glace
fruits, dried figs, coconut, dates, raisins, currants.; VIOLA'S SHERRIED
WALNUTS; 1 1/2 cups sugar; 1/2 cup cream sherry; 1 teaspoon light corn syrup;
Pinch salt; 1 1/2 teaspoons grated lemon rind; 2 1/2  cups walnuts;  Combine
the sugar, sherry, corn syrup, salt and lemon rind in a small saucepan. Bring
to 238 degrees on a candy thermometer. Remove from heat and add the nuts,
stirring until the mixture turns creamy. Turn out onto an oiled cookie sheet
and break up with a fork. Allow to cool, then put into small gift tins. Makes
about 4 cups of nuts.;   Note: If you want to make more, repeat the process.
Do not double. Make up to a month before giving.; BOUQUET GARNI SACHETS; 1 jar
dried parsley flakes; 1 jar peppercorns; 1 jar dried thyme; 1 jar bay leaves;
1 jar dried rosemary; 1 jar dried tarragon;  Pour the spices into a bowl and
stir well to blend thoroughly. Remove labels from the bottles; return the
spices to the bottles. Replace labels with your own labels.;   Note: Use the
standard-size jar of each spice to make this mixture. Use the same brand so
you'll have equal amounts of each spice.;   To use: Place 2 tablespoons
mixture in 6-inch square of good cheesecloth and tie up with string, or use
mulling bags. Use in soups, stews, inside a roasting chicken or in a meat
roasting pan.;   Hint: When tying the cheesecloth, leave the string long so
that it can be tied to the handle of the pot, making the bouquet easy to
retrieve.; RUMTOPF; Blemish-free fruit (Including strawberries, raspberries,
peaches, apricots, apples, pears, melons, pineapple, cherries, or grapes, in
any combination); High-quality rum or brandy; Sugar (superfine dissolves
best);  Find a large, wide-mouth stoneware crock that will hold about 20
cups.;   Remove stones and cores from fruit, as well as peels if you desire.
Cut fruit to uniform size, about the same size as the strawberries.;   Start
with 2 pounds of fresh strawberries. Sprinkle with 1 pound of sugar and let
stand overnight on the counter. Pour into the container, then just cover with
brandy or rum. Cover with plastic wrap and weight down with a saucer or other
object so the fruit is submerged.;   As you find good fruit, keep adding to
the pot, together with half the fruit's weight in sugar. Add liquor to cover
each addition.;   The rumtopf should be full by 1 month before <DATE>Christmas</DATE>.
Cover with plastic wrap and leave a month in a cool, dark place.;   Note: You
can either spoon out the mixture into gift jars or, if you have the jars ahead
of time, you can do the whole process in individual jars by dividing the
fruit, sugar and liquor among them.;   Serving tips: This is a marvelous sauce
for ice cream or pound cake. Or, serve with crepes.; LEBKUCHEN; 1 cup honey;
3/4 cup packed dark brown sugar; 1 egg; 1 tablespoon lemon juice; Grated peel
of 1 lemon; 2 1/3 cups flour; 1 teaspoon cinnamon; 1/2 teaspoon ground
allspice; 1/2 teaspoon ground cloves; 1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg; 1/2 teaspoon
salt; 1/2 teaspoon baking soda; 1 cup sliced almonds or whole blanched
almonds; Glaze (recipe follows);  Heat honey until bubbling. Remove from heat
and cool slightly, then beat in the sugar, egg, lemon juice and peel; set
aside until lukewarm. Combine flour, seasonings and baking soda; add the honey
mixture and stir well to blend. Cover and refrigerate from 8 hours to 2 days.;
  Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Shape dough into 1-inch balls. Set them 2
inches apart on a cookie sheet lined with baking paper. Press flat with the
bottom of a wet glass. Press in 1 or 2 almond slices or 1 whole almond. Bake
for 12 to 15 minutes or until golden brown. Brush with glaze while still warm,
then allow to cool. Store in airtight containers for a few weeks. These
cookies start out hard and soften as they mature. Makes about 50 cookies.;  
Glaze: Combine 1 cup confectioners' sugar and 4 to 5 tablespoons water,
stirring to make a runny glaze.;   Note: Make cookies a month to six weeks
before giving.; MULLING SPICE; 12 cinnamon sticks; 1/4 cup whole cloves; 1
tablespoon nutmeg; 1 tablespoon cardamom; 1/4 cup allspice berries; 1/4 cup
juniper berries; Rind of 1 orange, cut into thin strips; Rind of 1 lemon, cut
into thin strips;  Mix all ingredients well, then divide into 6 mounds. Using
6-inch squares of good cheesecloth or 6 mulling bags, fill with the spices.
Tie the cloth or bags with string. (Leave string long so packet can be
retrieved easily.);   To use: Drop 1 bag into 1 quart cider or wine and heat.
(Do not bring to boil.) If using wine, try a hearty burgundy or an Italian
rose.;   Variation: For sweet mulling spice, add 1 cup dark brown sugar.  </TEXT>
