<LEADPARA>  CUSTOM-MADE holiday gifts from your kitchen are downright trendy this year.;  
You can be sure there will be no duplications in the gift pile. They cost less
than a store-bought gift. And they show both thought and effort.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DON'T WAIT FOR THE HOLIDAYS; START MAKING PRESENTS
NOW  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Kyra Effren is a Dallas free-lance writer. The last two ideas are from "Betty
Crocker's Christmas Book."  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The disadvantage of making gifts is that you usually remember to start
every Hanukkah or during the busy Christmas season. You end up trying to pull
something together in the middle of the night, or give up and promise you'll
do it next year.;   Well, this is next year, and here is a chance to get a
head start.;   Remember that packaging is important. Look for pretty bottles,
tins, plates and jars to dress up your gift. Scour second-hand shops and
stores that specialize in storage.;   Wrap the container in tissue, cellophane
or ribbon, or arrange several items in a basket. Add a label with a
description of the item, a use-by date and storage instruction. Recipes and
ideas on how to use the gift also are appreciated.;   Easy gift ideas;   (box)
 Herbs de Provence Spice Mix: Combine 3 tablespoons dried marjoram, 3
tablespoons dried thyme, 3 tablespoons dried savory, 1 tablespoon dried basil,
1 teaspoon dried rosemary, 1/2 teaspoon dried sage and 1/2 teaspoon fennel
seeds. Mix well and spoon into small jars. Makes 3/4 cup. Use to season
chicken, vegetables or meat.;   (box)  Herb Vinegar: Place 2 or 3 sprigs fresh
herb of choice in each bottle. Fill with red or white wine vinegar. Close
tightly and store in a cool, dark place. Vinegar will be ready in 2 months.
Use in dressings or where herbs and vinegar are called for in a recipe.;  
Suggested combinations for herb vinegars: basil with red wine vinegar;
tarragon or parsley with white wine vinegar; basil and oregano in red wine
vinegar for Italian vinegar; rosemary in either kind; star anise in rice
vinegar for Oriental vinegar.;   (box)  Homemade Vinegar: Pour 1/4 cup
commercial red wine vinegar into a wine bottle. Add leftover red wine
(unsweetened, unfortified), adding more as you have leftover red wine. When
the bottle is full, cover with cheesecloth and tie with rubber band. Store for
1 month or more at room temperature. When mature, carefully pour into gift
bottles. If sediment forms, strain through a cheesecloth-lined funnel.;  
(box)  Honey Mustard: Stir together 1 cup honey, 1/2 cup Dijon-style mustard
and 6 tablespoons red wine vinegar. Add salt, pepper and nutmeg to taste. Fill
gift jars and label. Refrigerate. Makes 4 ( 1/2 cup) jars. Makes a good
sandwich spread or an accompaniment to meats and chicken.;   (box)  Gourmet
Olives: Combine 2 jars (about 7 ounces each) drained large green olives and 2
cans (about 7 ounces each) ripe olives in a large jar. Mix together 3/4 cup
vegetable oil with 3 tablespoons vinegar, 1 tablespoon lemon juice, 3 cloves
of finely chopped garlic and 10 crushed peppercorns. Pour over olives and
refrigerate 10-12 hours. Shake olives occasionally to coat evenly. Divide into
jars. Makes about 3 cups.;   (box) Cranberry Cordials: Mix 2 (12-ounce)
packages chopped frozen cranberries with 4 cups sugar and 3 cups vodka in a
2-quart jar or crock. Cover tightly. Let stand at room temperature 2 weeks,
stirring or inverting jar every day. Strain, pour into cordial bottles and
seal. Makes 5 cups.  </TEXT>
