<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week
See also related article on page 1E of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  a bowl of steaming chili,; perhaps with a beer chaser; PEDERNALES RIVER CHILI;
4pounds lean beef, coarse chili grind; 1 large onion, coarsely chopped; 2
medium cloves garlic, finely chopped; 1 teaspoon salt, or to taste; 1 teaspoon
dried oregano (preferably Mexican); 1 teaspoon ground cumin; 2 cups boiling
water;  28-ounce can whole tomatoes, drained; 4 tablespoons ground hot red
chili; 2 tablespoons ground mild red chili;   Put meat in a large saute pan
over medium-high heat, break up any lumps with a fork and cook, stirring
occasionally until the meat is evenly browned. Drain fat. Add the onions and
garlic and cook until the onions are translucent. Stir in the salt, oregano,
cumin, water, and tomatoes. Gradually stir in the ground chilies, testing
until you achieve the degree of strength and flavor that suits your palate.
Bring to a boil, then lower heat and simmer, uncovered, for 1 hour. Stir
occasionally. Makes 8 servings.;    Note: Reported to have been <PERSON>Lyndon B.
Johnson</PERSON>'s favorite, this recipe comes from deep in the heart of <LOCATION>Texas.</LOCATION>;    --
From "Chili Madness" by; <PERSON>Jane Butel</PERSON> (<PERSON>Workman</PERSON> Publish-; ing, <DATE>1980</DATE>);  <LOCATION>TURKEY</LOCATION>
CHILI; 1 tablespoon vegetable oil; 1 onion, peeled and chopped; 3 garlic
cloves, peeled and minced; 1 red bell pepper, seeds and ribs removed, finely
diced; 1 green bell pepper, seeds and ribs removed, finely diced; 1 1/2 pounds
ground turkey; 2 tablespoons flour; 3 tablespoons chili powder; 2 tablespoons
ground cumin; 2 teaspoons powdered cocoa;  3/4 to 2 teaspoons cayenne pepper,
depending on desired strength;  1/4 cup tarragon vinegar; 2 tablespoons strong
brewed coffee; 2 14-ounce cans plum tomatoes, crushed;  1/4 teaspoon salt; 2
cups cooked black beans;   Heat the oil over medium-high heat in a Dutch oven
or deep skillet. Add onion, garlic and red and green bell peppers; saute,
stirring frequently, for 5 minutes. Add the ground turkey and saute for 5
minutes, stirring constantly and breaking up any lumps with a spoon.;    Stir
in flour, chili powder, cumin and cocoa. Cook over low heat, stirring
frequently, for 3 minutes to cook the spices. Add the remaining ingredients
except the black beans and bring to a boil over medium heat. Simmer the chili,
stirring occasionally, for 40 to 45 minutes, until thick and the turkey is
tender. Add the black beans and cook for 5 additional minutes. Makes 6
servings.;    -- From "The Gourmet Ga-; zelle Cookbook" by <PERSON>Ellen Brown</PERSON>;
(<ORGANIZATION>Bantam Books</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>1989</DATE>);  NAVAJO GREEN CHILI; 3 pounds pork shoulder, fat and
bone removed, cut into 1/2-inch cubes (reserve fat); 1  to 3 cups flour in a
heavy paper bag; 3 medium onions, coarsely chopped; 4 medium cloves garlic,
finely chopped; 2 16-ounce cans whole green chilies, drained, seeded and cut
into 2-inch slices; 2 16-ounce cans whole tomatoes; 1 6-ounce can tomato
paste; 3 cups water; 1 teaspoon salt, or to taste;  1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
(preferably Mexican);   Melt the pork fat in a heavy skillet over medium-high
heat. Coat the pork cubes with flour by shaking them in the flour-filled paper
bag. Add the cubes to the skillet a few at a time, stirring to brown evenly.
Remove the cubes to a 5-quart Dutch oven or other heavy pot. Continue browning
the pork cubes in the skillet until all are browned. Add the onions and garlic
to the skillet. Cook, stirring occasionally, until the onions are translucent.
Add to the pot with the pork. Stir the remaining ingredients into the
pork-and-onion mixture. Bring to a boil, then lower the heat and simmer,
uncovered, for 1/2 hour. Taste, adjust seasonings and cook for 1/2 hour
longer. Makes 6 servings.;    Note: Go light on the peppers when starting out;
you can always add more.;    -- From "Chili Madness" by; <PERSON>Jane Butel</PERSON> (<PERSON>Workman</PERSON>
Publish-; ing, <DATE>1980</DATE>);  <PERSON>DAVE SCHWARDON</PERSON>'S; SUPERSONIC TONIC; 2 1/2 pounds beef
brisket, well trimmed; 2 tablespoons olive oil, divided; 1 large onion,
chopped; 1 small Italian frying pepper, chopped; 5 cloves garlic, quartered; 
1/2 pound pork; 2 tablespoons chopped canned green chiles; 1 tablespoon ground
cumin;  Pinch oregano; 1 1/2 teaspoons dry mustard;  1/2 cup tomato sauce; 8
ounces canned whole tomatoes; 1 tablespoon tequila;  1/2 cup beer; 4
tablespoons chili powder;  1/2 beef bouillon cube;  1/2 teaspoon brown sugar;
3 tablespoons 101-proof bourbon; 1 ounce canned, small hot chile peppers,
whole;  <LOCATION>Saltines</LOCATION>;   Cut brisket into 1/2-inch cubes. In a large skillet, heat
1 tablespoon oil. Add beef; saute until brown. Transfer meat to a 4-quart
pot.;    Add remaining olive oil to skillet and saute onion, pepper and garlic
until soft. Add to beef in pot. Cutpork into 1/2-inch cubes and add to
skillet. Cook, stirring constantly, until browned. Drain off and discard fat.
Add pork to pot.;    Add chiles, cumin, oregano, mustard, tomato sauce, whole
tomatoes, tequila, beer, chili powder, bouillon cube, brown sugar, bourbon and
chile peppers to pot. Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer, covered, until
meat is tender. Serve with saltines. Makes 8 servings.; <ORGANIZATION>NEIMAN</ORGANIZATION>'S <LOCATION>TEXAS</LOCATION> WHITE
CHILI; 1 pound dried white beans; 1 1/2 quarts chicken stock; 1 1/2 medium
onions, chopped; 2 cloves garlic, chopped; 1 teaspoon salt; 1 tablespoon corn
oil; 1 4-ounce can green chiles, chopped; 2 teaspoons each: ground cumin,
crushed dried oregano and ground coriander;  Pinch each: ground cloves and
cayenne; 4 boneless, skinless cooked chicken breasts, diced;  1/2 cup grated
Monterey jack cheese; 4 green onions, thinly sliced;   Combine beans, stock,
half the onion, garlic and salt in a large kettle and bring to a boil. Reduce
heat, cover and simmer 1 1/2 hours or until beans are very tender, adding more
chicken stock as needed.;    Heat oil in a skillet. Add the remaining chopped
onion and cook until tender and clear, about 5 minutes. Add the chopped
chiles, cumin, oregano, coriander, cloves and cayenne and mix thoroughly. Cook
20 minutes more. Add the skillet mixture to bean mixture. Portion chicken into
4 servings. For each serving, put chicken in bottom of bowl, spoon chili over
the top and sprinkle with the grated cheese and sliced green onion. Serves 4.;
   -- <LOCATION>Houston Chronicle</LOCATION>;  BLACK BEAN CHILI; 4 cups black beans; 3 cups canned
crushed whole tomatoes; 2 large finely chopped yellow onions; 1 1/2 cups
finely chopped green bell peppers;  1/2 cup olive oil; 2 tablespoons cumin
seed; 2 tablespoons oregano; 1 teaspoon cayenne pepper; 1 1/2 tablespoons
paprika;  1/2 cup finely chopped jalapeno peppers (canned are fine); 2 cloves
garlic, minced; 1 teaspoon salt;  1/2 pound Jack or cheddar cheese, grated; 
1/2 cup green onions, finely chopped;  2/3 cup sour cream; 8 sprigs cilantro,
optional;   Pick through and rinse beans. Cover with water in a large pot and
bring to a boil. Simmer 1 3/4 hours or until tender. Strain, reserving 1 cup
liquid. Add back to beans. Toast cumin and oregano in a 325-degree oven for 10
to 12 minutes, or until toasty.;    Saute onions, green peppers and garlic in
oil with cumin, oregano, cayenne, paprika and salt, 10 minutes. Add tomatoes
and chiles. Add all to the beans and stir.;    To serve, place 1 ounce grated
cheese, then 1 1/4 cups hot chili in heated bowl. Top with sour cream.
Sprinkle with green onions and a sprig of cilantro. Serves 8.; -- <LOCATION>Cafe
Beaujolais</LOCATION>,; <LOCATION>Mendocino</LOCATION>  </TEXT>
